<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Maradona Tests Positive for Cocaine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, Uruguay, Jan 5 (Xinhua) -- Hospitalized Argentine
soccer star Diego Maradona has tested positive fro cocaine with
his blood and urine samples after he checked into a Uruguayan
hospital with blood pressure and heart problem, a chief police
officers said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"I have been authorized by a judge to inform you that our test
(blood and urine) has resulted positive for cocaine," Maximo Costa
Rocha, police chief for the Uruguayan province of Maldonado, told
a news conference.
</P>
<P>
Maradona was admitted to the intensive care unit of a hospital
in the Uruguayan resort town of Punta del Este on Tuesday
suffering from what his doctor called hypertension and an
irregular heartbeat.
</P>
<P>
The 39-year-old soccer star who led Argentina to victory in the
1986 World Cup final against Germany has a long history of drug
abuse.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rocha said Maradona had not been arrested but that
investigations were continuing. A second drug test was being
analysed, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000106.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Maintains Condemnation of Coup in Cote d'Ivoire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Foreign Minister Alhaji
Sule Lamido said Wednesday that his government maintains its
condemnation of the military take-over in Cote d'Ivoire.
</P>
<P>
Lamido, who is among 10 ministers sent to Abidjanent Henri
Konan Bedie.
</P>
<P>
He noted that if military coups are left unchallenged, "then
democracy would never see the light of day as soldiers could just
wake up one morning and use force to bring down a government
chosen by the people."
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian minister urged the military junta of Cote d'Ivoire
to restore democracy within the shortest time, saying that six
months would be enough for the junta to hand over power to
civilians, as it was done in Mali and recently in Niger.
</P>
<P>
Lamido pointed out that Nigeria, which has just emerged from
15- year military rule, would be willing to assist Cote d'Ivoire
to restore democracy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
