<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Damascus Radio on Syrian-Israeli Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Syria considers peace elements
as an integrated indivisible whole based on the principle of total
Israeli withdrawal from the Golan Heights and south Lebanon,
Damascus Radio said in its political commentary Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Everybody has to know that Syria embarked on the peace talks
because it wants to establish a fair and comprehensive peace," the
radio said, noting that Syria can not compromise on its territories
since peace can not coexist with occupation.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday in Shephersdtown, West Virginia of the United
States, Syrian and Israeli negotiators started negotiating on such
crucial issues as the demarcation of the June 4, 1967 border lines,
the water, security arrangements, the normalization of Syrian-
Israeli relations and the time-table of the implementation of the
expected peace deal.
</P>
<P>
"Peace will not be achieved except through Israel's withdrawal
from the Golan Heights and south Lebanon" and peace talks on the
Syrian and Lebanese tracks are parallel, said the radio.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and Syria, a power broker which deploys about 30,000
troops in Lebanon as peace-keepers, have insisted on the
integration of their talks with Israel.
</P>
<P>
"Any attempt to undermine such equilibrium will not serve the
desired peace and will rather abort the peace efforts," the radio
added.
</P>
<P>
It underlined that Syria did not ask Israel to make any
concession during the ongoing talks which started on Tuesday.
However, Syria insists on its legitimate rights to restore its
occupied territories.
</P>
<P>
Israel is now in control of Syria's Golan Heights captured
during the 1967 Mideast war. It also has been holding a border
strip in south Lebanon of about 1,100 square kilometers since 1985.
</P>
<P>
Syria sticks to the principle of equal footing while working out
the security arrangements with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Syria is very serious about its pursuit of peace. In the
meantime it can never accept any attempt by Israel to foil "the
peace equation" or to foul up the priorities of the peace talks,
said the radio.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday Syrian and Israeli negotiators continued their
talks in Shepherdstown after U.S. President Bill Clinton managed to
remove the obstacle of the first day of the talks. The dispute was
related to the talks agenda issues.
</P>
<P>
While the Syrian side insisted on putting the Israeli withdrawal
from the Golan Heights atop the agenda, the Israeli side insisted
on discussing the security arrangements first. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000106.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Commission Adopts Presidential Elections Schedule </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Officially, campaigning for the race for the Kremlin started
Thursday, said Olga Zastrozhnaya, secretary of the commission.
</P>
<P>
The polls, originally scheduled for next June, were moved up
following the abrupt resignation of Former President Boris Yeltsin
on New Year's Eve. Yeltsin has named his preferred successor,
Prime Minister Vladimir Putin, as acting president.
</P>
<P>
Putin, already the most popular politician in post-Soviet
Russia, will almost certainly win the elections, as the
abbreviated campaign left him with the advantages of incumbency
and his opponents with much less time to act.
</P>
<P>
The campaign will now last for 81 days, and applications for
nomination of candidates must be filed "no earlier than January 18
and no later that 18:00 local time on February 13," Zastrozhnaya
said.
</P>
<P>
Canvassing is to stop at midnight on March 24, and candidates
must provide information not only about their incomes, but also
about those of their spouses and other family members, she said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to Putin, others that have declared their readiness
to run include Communist Party leader Gennady Zyuganov, liberal
Yabloko leader Grigory Yavlinsky, and ultra-nationalist Vladimir
Zhirinovsky.
</P>
<P>
Former Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov, who had declared his
readiness to run for president before the December 19 State Duma
parliamentary elections, an attempt to win more votes for the
Fatherland-All Russia election bloc that he heads.
</P>
<P>
However, the All Russia movement of regional leaders that made
up the Fatherland- All Russia, has indicated it would support
Putin's bid for the Kremlin, and urged Primakov to vie for speaker
of the State Duma instead. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000106.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> United Nations Concerned Over Cambodia Draft Law on Trials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations still
has concerns about Cambodia's draft law on the trial of members of
the Khmer Rouge, U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Eckhard said Hans Corell, the United Nations Legal Counsel, met
this morning with the Permanent Representative of Cambodia,
Ambassador Borith Ouch, to hand over the United Nations' comments
on the second draft of a Cambodian law concerning the trial of
members of the Khmer Rouge.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was timed to permit these comments to be forwarded
to the Cambodian Cabinet, which was to meet shortly after, said
the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
" The thrust of those comments was that the United Nations still
had concerns about the draft law," he said.
</P>
<P>
At the same meeting, Corell transmitted a letter to the
Permanent Representative inviting the Government of Cambodia to
send as early as possible its representatives to New York to
resume discussion of the outstanding issues, and the intention is
to agree on a text that would meet international standards of
justice, fairness and the due process of law, Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that discussions can continue, and eventually we can
agree on a draft that meets international standards," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
