<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bomb Removed From Moscow Apartment Block </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Security agents removed a bomb
Thursday evening from an apartment block in central Moscow, the
Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Two TNT charges with detonators were planted on the ground
floor of a four-story building on Bolshoi Kozikhinsky Pereulok,
Interfax said, citing law enforcement sources.
</P>
<P>
Tenants were evacuated from their apartments and traffic along
the road was suspended after the bomb was found.
</P>
<P>
Moscow witnessed several major apartment bombings last year.
Over 200 people were killed in two separate blasts in the capital
city on September 8 and 12. Authorities said terrorists with links
to Chechen rebels were behind the attacks.
</P>
<P>
The blasts and similar attacks in two other Russian cities were
eventually followed by a federal military campaign against rebels
in the breakaway republic of Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
Security has since been beefed up in Moscow and around the
country, especially near vital installations such as nuclear power
plants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000106.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Reports on Declining Populations Forthcoming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Population Division on Thursday issued an information sheet about
a forthcoming study on declining and aging populations.
</P>
<P>
The study examined aging and population decline in eight
countries -- France, Germany, Italy, Japan, the Republic of Korea,
the Russia Federation, the United Kingdom and the United States --
and a preliminary report on the study's findings is expected by
the end of March.
</P>
<P>
In the information sheet, the Population Division noted that
the countries of Europe, as well as Japan, are expected to decline
in population size over the next 50 years.
</P>
<P>
It said Italy, with a current population of 57 million, is
projected to reach 41 million by 2050, while Russia is projected
to decrease from 147 million people to 121 million over the next
50 years.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, Japan, which now has 127 million people, is expected
to have a population of 105 million by 2050, the information sheet
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000106.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Economic Growth Slows Down in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean economy is forecast to
grow at a lower rate in 1999 than expected, because of the
unstable macro- economic environment, poor commodity prices and a
decline in agricultural output.
</P>
<P>
The economy was estimated to grow by 1.2 percent in 1999
compared to 1.5 percent recorded in the previous year, Finhold, a
leading local finance house, said in its 1999 annual report
released here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The expected lower growth was attributed specifically to high
levels of inflation and interest rates as well as foreign currency
shortages arising from depressed commodity prices of the country's
major exports.
</P>
<P>
The suspension of the remainder of the 176-million-U.S. dollar
International Monetary Fund (IMF) stand-by arrangement in the last
quarter of 1998 compounded the problems afflicting the Zimbabwean
economy.
</P>
<P>
The anticipated additional foreign currency inflows from other
bilateral and multi-lateral donors largely failed to materialize.
</P>
<P>
"Consequently, the 1998/99 financial year witnessed a further
depreciation of the Zimbabwean dollar which in turn had a negative
effect on those sectors of the economy that are import-intensive
in terms of inputs," the report said.
</P>
<P>
Finhold urged the Zimbabwean government to pursue policies that
 stimulate growth in the real sectors of the economy in order to
boost overall economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Such policies include the implementation of contradictory
fiscal policies that are supportive of the tight monetary policies
of recent years.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean government was also recommended to be prudent to
 accelerate the privatization of parastatals and use the proceeds
to reduce the stock of domestic debt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000106.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwandan Parliament Speaker Asked to Resign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The speaker of the Rwandan
parliament Joseph Sebarenzi Kabuye has been asked to resign by 86
percent of the parliamentarians, Rwanda News Agency(RNA) reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In a nine-page letter signed on Wednesday by 60 out of 70
deputies that make up the National Assembly enumerated several
mistakes attributed to the speaker, advising him to "immediately
resign instead of losing his reputation if normal procedures are
to be followed".
</P>
<P>
The parliamentarians accuse him among others, of dictatorial
tendencies, flouting procedure in the conduct of house business,
inducing unnecessary disagreements between the Parliament and
other political institutions, and mismanagement of Assembly's
funds.
</P>
<P>
According to the Assembly's Internal regulations, the speaker
upon receipt of the letter is supposed to call an extraordinary
session within 7 days to debate on the content of the letter
before a vote is carried out to determine whether he retains or
lose confidence of the parliamentarians.
</P>
<P>
Political analysts in the capital Kigali say Sebarenzi Kabuye
will not escape this move because the majority of deputies have
expressed no confidence in him. But a parliamentary source close
to the speaker who asked for anonymity told RNA "there is some
possibility of the situation to reverse because a vote in the
Parliament is secret".
</P>
<P>
If his resignation is realized, be it by passing vote of no
confidence or by his own initiative, Sebarenzi will be the second
speaker to have lost confidence of the parliamentarians and
subsequently asked to resign since the Transitional Assembly
started operating on November 25 1994.
</P>
<P>
Sebarenzi, from the Liberal Party was appointed speaker of the
National Assembly on March 3, 1997 after his predecessor Juvenal
Nkusi was also forced to resign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
