<HEADLINE> Uganda Peaceful Despite Rebel Incursions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's Inspector General of
Police John Kisembo said Thursday the country is relatively calm
and peaceful in spite of incursions of small groups of rebels in
the northern and western parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening of the ninth police training course at
Kibuli Police School here, Kisembo said the relative instability
in some parts caused by the recent incursions of small groups of
rebels would not destabilize the whole country.
</P>
<P>
The rebels of the Allied Democratic Forces and the Lord's
Resistance Army in the western and northern parts of the country
respectively would be wiped out by the government troops, he said.
</P>
<P>
To reinforce the police force, a total of more than 3,000 new
recruits will be made this year, he said. Some of the new
recruits are already undergoing necessary training, he added.
</P>
<P>
The police chief also urged the 15,000-strong police force to
improve their image marred by rampant corruption. 
