<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- The Lebanese government is expected to spend about 5.6
billion U.S. dollars in the year 2000 and to generate about 3.6
billion dollars, leaving a spending deficit of 36 percent, the
Daily Star newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The year 2000 budget proposal, to be approved by the parliament
this month, suggested the privatization of state-run companies.
</P>
<P>
It was based on reducing current expenditures, increasing
revenues and stabilizing the costs of public employment through
privatization and administrative reforms.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Total foreign reserves at Lebanon's Central Bank stood
at 10.2 billion U.S. dollars by the end of last November, the Daily
Star newspaper Thursday quoted a report by the bank as saying.
</P>
<P>
Due to the growing trend of saving in Lebanese pounds, the
bank's international reserves, including gold and net of foreign
liabilities, rose 34.3 million dollars in November, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese pound was stable in November, with the dollar/pound
rate staying at 1,507.5.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt's Public Authority for Investment is expected to
declare within days its final approval for the establishment of the
Suez Canal Containers Company with an issued capital of 55 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The company will be set up after the National Bank, which is the
agent of the founders, completes the establishment procedures, the
Alalam Alyom daily reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It will undertake the management, operation and possession of
containers passing the Suez Canal.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- Saudi General Authority for Ports opened a website on
the Internet in a bid to attract more ships to Saudi ports by
showing the services available and 183 platforms capable of
receiving the most sophisticated vessels and handling all kinds of
goods.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi ports receive 12,000 ships every year to load and
unload 90 million tons of goods.
</P>
<P>
The website contains general information about the Authority and
the role it has been playing in running and developing the Saudi
ports during the past 24 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
