<HEADLINE> Russian Exporters to Convert All Earnings Into Rubles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Russian Acting President Vladimir
Putin on Thursday approved a proposal of the Central Bank that
will require the country's exporters to convert all of their hard
currency earnings into rubles.
</P>
<P>
"This is a step in the right direction," Putin said after a
meeting with Viktor Geraschenko, chairman of the Central Bank, the
Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
However, Putin, who continues to serve as prime minister, said
"any decision ought to be calculated. It must not be made without
stepping up currency and export controls, and must not hurt
exports."
</P>
<P>
The exporters are now required to convert only 75 percent of
their foreign exchange revenues into rubles, which officially
stood at 27.23 to the U.S. dollar Thursday. They are allowed to
retain the remaining 25 percent to make equipment purchases abroad.
</P>
<P>
"The State Duma should also have a hand in the process," Putin
said, adding that imposing a law on the export proceeds sales
would be desirable.
</P>
<P>
Russia first introduced the rules on forced sales of hard
currency earnings after a financial crisis in 1998, when very few
companies were voluntarily buying into the depreciating rubles.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Putin and Geraschenko also discussed the
possibility of lowering the refinancing rate. Putin said if it
happened, the reduction would "be a very good sign for the economy,
the financial market and the real sector." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
