<HEADLINE> Canadians Urged to Donate Y2K Food to Food Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Canadians are being urged to
donate their stockpiled food to food banks across the country.
</P>
<P>
Food bank directors in Toronto, Calgary, Vancouver and some
other cities are welcoming the donation following the bust of the
predicted Y2K calamity, Local media said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
This is a time of year when there is always a great demand for
food. What is more, most provinces issued welfare cheques early
last month in case of Y2K glitches, creating an even greater
demand for food, directors say.
</P>
<P>
In Vancouver, food bank officials want residents to drop off
non-perishable food at local grocery stores, while Toronto's food
bank is asking for excess food to be brought to fire halls this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
Chris Harris, executive director of the Calgary Inter-faith
Food Bank, said several utility corporations bought cases of
canned food to keep their teams fed for days.
</P>
<P>
"The question is do they still need it, and if they don't we'd
very much like it," he was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
In Halifax, Nova Scotia, food bank officials "undoubtedly"
believe that people have stocked up and are now left with a
surplus.
</P>
<P>
"We would be delighted if those people could share," said Mel
Boutilier, director of Halifax's food bank.
</P>
<P>
People began hoarding Y2K items months before the New Year.
Nearly everything was bought just in case, including generators,
gas masks, lamp oil, toilet paper, bottled water, canned goods and
powdered milk, according to the local media. 
</P>
</TEXT>
