<HEADLINE> British Home Secretary Defends Action over Nazi Suspect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Straw was commenting on criticism from Nazi hunters angered
that Kalejs was allowed to leave Britain for Australia on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
They said Kalejs was a member of a Nazi-run Latvian hit squad
responsible for 30,000 deaths during World War Two and should be
prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
Straw said the information he received about Kalejs, who has
been an Australian citizen since 1957, had justified launching
deportation proceedings against him but criminal prosecution would
require a far higher standard of evidence.
</P>
<P>
He added that the decision not to charge him was entirely a
matter for police.
</P>
<P>
"It has never been the role of the Home Secretary to second
guess police over whether to pursue charges," the Reuters quoted
him as saying. "Detailed matters of evidence are a question for
the police, not me." 
</P>
