<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambican Opposition Confirms Boycott of New Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Mozambican National
Resistance (Renamo) , main opposition party of the country, has
confirmed that it will boycott the opening session of the
country's newly-elected parliament, the Assembly of the Republic,
scheduled for January 14.
</P>
<P>
Renamo General-secretary Joao Alexandre told Radio Mozambique
Thursday that the 117 deputies from Renamo and its allies in the
"Electoral Union" will not take their seats in the assembly.
</P>
<P>
The "Electoral Union" consists of Renamo plus ten minor
parties.
</P>
<P>
He said that the coalition is waiting for a dialogue with the
ruling Mozambique Liberation Front Party (Frelimo) in order to
achieve a platform of understanding.
</P>
<P>
"Our deputies will not attend the opening session, nor will
they take their seats until the votes have been recounted,"
Alexandre said.
</P>
<P>
Renamo called for a recount of the results of the elections
held on December 3-5, 1999. But the Supreme Court ruled against
Renamo and validated the election results announced by the
National Elections Commission.
</P>
<P>
According to the officially announced results, Frelimo and
incumbent President Joaquim Chissano won the second multi-party
elections of the southern African country since 1994.
</P>
<P>
Both President Chissano and Frelimo General Secretary Manuel
Tome have made it clear that the country cannot grind to a halt
just because Renamo disagrees with the Supreme Court's ruling.
</P>
<P>
They held that the Frelimo deputies will take their seats and
parliamentary business will start with or without Renamo's
presence.
</P>
<P>
Since there is no further appeal against the Supreme Court's
ruling, there is nothing further that Renamo can do.
</P>
<P>
The assembly can function without Renamo since Frelimo holds
133 of the 250 seats, exceeding the quorum of 126 (50 percent plus
one).
</P>
<P>
However, it is not clear whether Renamo will be able to oblige
all its coalition partners to adhere to the boycott. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
