<HEADLINE> U.N. Security Council to Hold Special Session on Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Security
Council will realize a special session on Angola this month,
analyzing the political- military situation in the southern
African country, U.S. Ambassador to Angola Joseph Sullivan said
here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador said in a local radio program that the meeting
will be held in an ambit of promise created by the visit to Angola
by U.S. Ambassador to United Nations Richard Holbrook last
December.
</P>
<P>
According to Sullivan, the meeting will map out new measures
for the implementation of the U.N. sanctions against Jonas Savimbi
and his rebel National Union for Total Independence of Angola
(UNITA).
</P>
<P>
The humanitarian situation and issues on AIDS will also be
discussed by the participants of the special meeting to be
presided over by the U.S. which will take the rotating presidency
of the U.N. Security Council in January.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. said that during its term of office, the Security
Council will give priority to the issues on Africa, a continent
heavily tormented by long-term conflicts and humanitarian
catastrophes. 
</P>
