<HEADLINE> Mozambique Issues Warning on Possible Flooding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Mozambican authorities have
warned of the possibility of flooding in the valley of the
Incomati River, the largest river in southern part of the country,
the Mozambique News Agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Southern Regional Water Board also issued a warning that
people living near the bank of the river should seek higher
ground.
</P>
<P>
According to the water board, by Tuesday the river was flowing
at 500 cubic meters per second at Ressano Garcia, the point where
it enters Mozambique from South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The water level of Incomati was 4.6 meters high, just 40
centimeters short of the maximum alert level of five meters. The
water level dropped slightly late Tuesday and early Wednesday and
the river was flowing at 440 meters per second.
</P>
<P>
However, the level of the Incomati is almost certain to rise
again substantially because the Driekopies dam in South Africa may
be forced to open its floodgates Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Mozambican water board noted that the reservoir was 99
percent full on Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Because there are no dams on the Mozambican part of Incomati,
any flood wave entering the country at Ressano Garcia will travel
for the full length until it reaches the sea at Marracuene, a
district of Southern Mozambique. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
