<HEADLINE> Congo Rebels Accused of Killing Civilians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Allied Forces fighting in the
 Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) said Thursday that the
rebels fighting to topple President Laurent Kabila continue
murdering civilians in the vast war-torn central African country.
</P>
<P>
The Allied Forces headquarters said in a statement that the
rebels murdered seven civilians in the Eshimba area in Kabinda
Saturday, the Zimbabwean News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
It said that the civilians were murdered after being accused by
the rebels of being informants of the Allied Forces because they
were related to the Kabinda district administrator.
</P>
<P>
Strongly condemning the "cowardly act" of the rebels, the
Allied Forces headquarters reminded the Congolese rebels and their
supporters of the need to observe the Lusaka Peace Agreement
signed by all the parties directly involved in the DRC conflict.
</P>
<P>
"The culprits shall be pursued to the bitter end," the Allied
Forces stressed.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia sent troops to the Congo in 1998
to beef up Kabila's army while Rwanda and Uganda have been
allegedly supporting the rebels in the 16-month war. 
</P>
