<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Opposition Urged to Support Parliamentary Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government
Thursday urged opposition political parties and civic
organizations to support the voters registration exercise for
parliamentary elections scheduled for March this year.
</P>
<P>
The registration process should be transparent, Home Affairs
Minister Dumiso Dabengwa told a meeting to discuss the modalities
and the role of opposition parties and civic organizations in the
exercise.
</P>
<P>
The exercise comes at a time when the country is preparing for
the referendum to adopt the country's draft constitution and the
parliamentary elections, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Dabengwa welcomed cooperation and assistance from the
opposition and civic organizations.
</P>
<P>
The registration exercise is due to kick off on January 15-29
although the Registrar-General's office would remain open to those
who would miss the exercise.
</P>
<P>
Although most participants appreciated the need for the
exercise, they said they were no longer comfortable with
Registrar-General Tobaiwa Mudede conducting the exercise as they
had lost confidence in him.
</P>
<P>
President of the Democratic Party Wurayayi Zembe said
opposition parties had met last year and agreed that the office of
the Registrar-General should be abolished and replaced by an
independent electoral commission before voters' registration could
be discussed. 
</P>
