<HEADLINE> Israel's Second Troop Redeployment Goes On Smoothly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 6 (Xinhua)-- The second-phase troop
redeployment by Israel Defense Force (IDF) on the West Bank are
proceeding smoothly and will be completed on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The IDF has already evacuated six military bases as part of the
troop withdrawal and two of them, Camp Yosef near the northern West
Bank city of Nablus and Camp Barak near Jenin, are now in the hands
of the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The IDF soldiers and the Palestinian security forces started
Thursday conducting joint patrols in the areas just transferred to
the Palestinians in the vicinities of Jenin, Ramallah and Hebron,
the IDF spokesman's office said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The two sides are working together to demarcate the new border
areas where the map has changed, and the IDF has been assigned to
put up signs warning Israelis that they are entering areas now
under Palestinian control along the new borders of area A, which is
totally under the Palestinian control, the office added.
</P>
<P>
The civil administration in these newly-handed-over areas will
actually be delivered to the Palestinians next Thursday, upon
request by the Palestinian side that Id al Fiter Holiday falls at
the weekend of this week.
</P>
<P>
Israel and the Palestinians reached an agreement on the 5
percent land transfer from the West Bank on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The redeployment includes transfer of 2 percent from Area B,
which Israel controls security and Palestinians exercise civil
administration, to Area A, and 3 percent from Israel's totally
controlled Area C to Area B.
</P>
<P>
The second withdrawal, initially scheduled for last November 15,
was postponed due to Palestinians' refusal to accept the areas
Israel was willing to hand over.
</P>
<P>
Under the compromise agreement reached Tuesday, the second
withdrawal should be carried out as originally planned by Israel,
while Israel will consider Palestinian requests in sketching the
maps for the third withdrawal on January 20.
</P>
<P>
Under the new peace deal signed by Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat in Sharm el Sheikh last
September, Israel will transfer another 11 percent of the West Bank
territories to the Palestinians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
