<DOCNO> XIE20000106.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. New-Home Sales Fall Sharply in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Commerce Department reported Thursday that the November's
drop in single-family sales followed a big 9 percent increase in
October. But Even with the setback, homes were sold at a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of 865,000 units in November, the
Department said.
</P>
<P>
New-home sales have been above an annual rate of 800,000 for a
record 23 straight months. The previous record was a five-month
string of sales at that level set in late 1977.
</P>
<P>
Many economists had been predicting a slowdown in the red-hot
housing market since June, when the Federal Reserve started
pushing interest rates higher in an effort to dampen such interest-
sensitive sectors of the economy as housing.
</P>
<P>
Last week, 30-year fixed-rate mortgages climbed to 8.06 percent,
compared to 6.83 percent at the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Although November's new-home sales had a setback, the biggest
decline since December 1997, housing sales remained above an
annual rate of 800,000 homes for a record 23rd straight month.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said since housing and consumer spending have remained
so strong, they were looking for the Federal Reserve to boost
interest rates further this year, possibly engineering another
three rate increases in an effort to slow economic activity and
keep inflation under control.
</P>
<P>
Even with the drop in homes sales, the price of a new home
continued to rise to record levels. The average price climbed 4.2
percent to a record 209,700 dollars. The median price also jumped
to a record of 167,400 dollars, up 5.3 percent from October.
</P>
<P>
Sales declines occurred in all parts of the country with the
Northeast suffering the biggest percentage decline, a drop of 31.5
percent which left sales in that region of the country at an
annual rate of 50,000 units, the slowest pace of activity since
January 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
