<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, January 6 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraqi President Saddam Hussein on Thursday said that
the United Nations embargo imposed on Iraq "has actually started"
to be corroded "thanks to the great fortitude and the endurance of
the Iraqi people."
</P>
<P>
Saddam made the remarks in a nationally televised address to
mark the 79th anniversary of the founding of the Iraqi National
Army.
</P>
<P>
He said "we have said it with certainty that the embargo will
not be lifted by a (U.N.) Security Council resolution, but will
corrode by itself."
</P>
<P>
Baghdad has long argued that it has carried out all its
commitments toward relevant U.N. resolutions, and demanded that
the Security Council lift the sanctions imposed on it since its
1990 invasion of Kuwait. (Iraq-Saddam-Address)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- Home Minister L. K. Advani announced Thursday that
four key associates of the five hijackers of an Indian Airlines
jet have been arrested in Mumbai.
</P>
<P>
The four, all Harkat-ul-Ansar operatives, are Mohd Rehan and
Mohd Iqbal (both Pakistani nationals), Yusuf Nepali (a Nepali
national) and Abdul Latif, an Indian.
</P>
<P>
The identity of the five hijackers has also been established
and they are all Pakistani nationals, Advani said.
</P>
<P>
The hijackers identified by these operatives are Ibrahim Athar
from Bahawalpur, Shahid Akhtar Sayed from Gulshan Iqbal of Karachi,
Sunny Ahmed Qazi from Defense Area of Karachi and Shaqir from
Sukkur City.
</P>
<P>
Advani said Athar is the brother of Maulana Masood Azhar, the
Pakistani cleric freed by India along with two other militants in
exchange for the hostages on the aircraft, which was hijacked on
Christmas Eve. (India-Hijackers)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- At least 12 people were injured in a bomb blast in
a train at the Old Delhi railway station Thursday afternoon,
police said.
</P>
<P>
The medium-intensity explosion took place in a compartment of
an express immediately after it reached the platform from the yard,
Deputy Commissioner of Police P.K. Srivastava said.
</P>
<P>
The blast shattered the window panes, ripped apart all the
seats and created a one-meter radius hole in the bogie, he said.
</P>
<P>
The train was for Saharanpur in the north state of Uttar
Pradesh.
</P>
<P>
He said the bomb might have been kept under a seat in one of
the second-class compartments.
</P>
<P>
A team from the Central Forensic Sciences Laboratory had
reached the spot to determine the nature of the explosive used in
the blast while a sniffer dog squad had also been pressed into
service to examine the spot, the Press Trust of India (PTI)
reported. (India-Blast) 
</P>
</TEXT>
