<HEADLINE> Silver Crashes by 130 Rupees in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Prices of silver crashed by
130 rupees (3.02 U.S dollars) per kilogram and gold fell by 30
rupees (0.7 dollar) per 10 grams on the bullion market Thursday in
Mumbai (Bombay) due to a steep fall in global prices.
</P>
<P>
Standard gold ended at 4,460 rupees (103.72 dollars) per 10
grams, showing a steep fall of 30 rupees (0.7 dollar) over the
last close of 4,490 rupees (104.42 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Twenty-two-carat gold was nominally quoted weaker at 4,125
rupees (95.93 dollars) per 10 grams from Wednesday's level of 4,
155 rupees (96.63 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, ready silver (.999 fineness) slumped by 130 rupees (
3.02 dollars) to close at 8,090 rupees (188.14 dollars) per
kilogram from the last close of 8,220 rupees (191.16 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Raw silver (.916 fineness) declined steeply by 140 rupees (3.25
dollars) to 7,960 rupees (185.12 dollars) per kilogram from 8,100
rupees (188.37 dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
