<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Stock Market Continues to Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Share prices nose-dived on
Singapore Stock Market Thursday after local stocks got one of
their worst-ever drubbings Wednesday following the sudden
resurgence of U.S. interest rate fears that triggered massive
plunges on Wall Street Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Time Index (STI) dropped 31.82 points to
close at 2,359.21, falling off its intra-day high of 2,425.57
points in Thursday's early trading.
</P>
<P>
Total volume decreased to 474.65 million shares worth 896.28
million Singapore dollars (539.77 million U.S. dollars). Losers
outstripped gainers by 278 to 81 with 138 counters unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Benefun topped the volume list as it registered a turnover of
32.97 million units. MediaRing was the second heavily-traded stock
with 29.72 million shares done. Hotung was the next with 24.73
million counters changing hands.
</P>
<P>
SPH and SPH 100 headed the ascent of the day and both rose 40
cents to close at 34.5 Singapore dollars. Venture edged up 20
cents to finish at 20.2 Singapore dollars. Global Tech and HL Fin
F inched up 12 cents to end at 2.51 and 3.12 Singapore dollars
respectively.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, PacCent remained at the top of the decliners'
list, dropping 260 cents to close at 16.3 Singapore dollars. SIA
DBScw00 was the second biggest loser of the day, incurring a loss
of 120 cents to finish at 12 Singapore dollars. SIA 200 fell 110
cents to end at 18.3 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the market opened higher but it failed to sustain
its opening gains as the Hong Kong and Tokyo markets made hefty
losses.
</P>
<P>
Brokers noted that investors were spooked by the regional sell-
down.
</P>
<P>
However, they said the decline was healthy given the market's
sharp ascent in recent trading sessions.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said all regional bourses were soundly thrashed
Wednesday, supposedly because of U.S. interest rate fears that led
to an overnight collapse on Wall Street but more likely because
prices had simply run up too far, too fast. 
</P>
</TEXT>
