<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Looted Food Trucks Recovered in S. Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Better organized security
guards from the International Red Cross and coalition militiamen
from the Rahanwein and Marehan clans have successfully recovered
two of three looted food trucks in southern Somalia.
</P>
<P>
After a heavy gunfire exchange between the rescue mission and
the looters, two looted trucks have been recovered, according to
information reaching here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A large food aid convoy in the Sakow district of Middle Jubba
region was ambushed Tuesday by the gunmen allegedly belonging to
Geledleh clan militiamen of the Rahanwein main community.
</P>
<P>
Clan elders who later on intervened into the situation have
pledged that the remaining truck would also be turned in, but the
fighting should be stopped first.
</P>
<P>
No exact casualty figures are available. However, information
from the area indicates that nearly a dozen people including
non-combatant civilians were either killed or wounded.
</P>
<P>
The food convoy consisted of over 30 heavy-duty trucks carrying
more than 300 tons of miscellaneous food items.
</P>
<P>
The gunmen succeeded in seizing three of the trucks during the
height of the fire exchange with the guards of the convoy who
escaped with the rest trucks towards the destined region of Gedo.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest reports, the survivor food convoy
reached the town of Bardera Wednesday on its ways to Garbaharrey
and Bur Dhubo towns where the final destination of the food aid
is.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, another large convoy of badly needed commercial
commodities including various food items reached Bardera town
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It took more than 30 days for the convoy to reach Bardera town
of the border Gedo region after leaving Mogadishu owing to mud and
insecurity along the road between Merca, Jilib and Bardera towns
of southern Somalia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
