<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU's Economic Sentiment Indicator Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission said
Thursday that the composite economic sentiment indicator for
December 1999 reveals a 0.1 point improvement in the euro zone and
a 0.4 point increase in the European Union as a whole, compared to
November.
</P>
<P>
Finland, Germany, the Netherlands and Britain, with 1.1, 0.6, 0.
4 and 0.4 point increases respectively, were the main contributors
to this improvement. Austria and Spain registered the biggest
declines with 1.1 and 0.4 points respectively.
</P>
<P>
The commission said in its business and consumer surveys that
Germany's manufacturing sector continued its upward trend in
December, which was initiated last August. Industrialist'
confidence in Italy and Britain is on the increase, too.
</P>
<P>
"Although France has reversed the rise observed in November,
confidence in the industrial sector remains steady in Europe," the
EU executive branch said.
</P>
<P>
The construction confidence indicator experienced a fall in
December, four points in both the EU and the euro zone, which
contrasts with the three consecutive rises observed in the
previous months. However, the present level is still well above
the long term average, the commission said.
</P>
<P>
Consumer confidence increased in the EU in December and
remained unchanged in the euro area, the EU executive added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000106.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Jobless Claims Rise by Largest Amount Last Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The number of people filing
new claims for jobless benefits in the country jumped by 33,000
last week, the largest increase in a year, the Labor Department
reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Department said the number of new applications for
unemployment benefits climbed to 309,000 for the week ending
Saturday,the figure has been above the 300,000-level for the first
time in 13 weeks. In the previous week, the claims had fallen by
7,000.
</P>
<P>
The Department's analysts explained that the claims level is
often volatile during holiday periods and they cautioned against
reading too much into one week's movement in jobless claims.
</P>
<P>
The increase of 33,000 for last week was the largest since a
jump of 60,000 for the week ending December 26, 1998, also a
period around the Christmas holidays.
</P>
<P>
The four-week moving average, which smoothes out weekly
volatility, was up by 3,500 to 283,750, still an extremely low
level indicating that labor markets remain tight.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. unemployment rate was at a 30-year low of 4.1 percent
in November and some analysts believe it may have dipped even
lower to 4 percent in December. That figure will be released by
the government Friday.
</P>
<P>
The dwindling pool of available workers has been cited by the
Federal Reserve as a major reason for raising interest rates three
times in the last six months.
</P>
<P>
Many economists are predicting even more interest-rate
increases in the new year as the central bank works to slow
economic growth as a way of taking pressure off labor markets and
keep rising wage demands from sparking inflationary pressures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
