<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU's Natural Increase of Population At Lowest Level </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, Jaunary 6 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) said
Thursday that its first demographic estimates indicate the natural
increase of the EU population was at its lowest level during the
post-war period.
</P>
<P>
The EU's statistical office, Eurostat, said the EU population
was 376.4 million on January 1, 2000. The increase of almost one
million inhabitants in 1999 was mainly due to a net migration of
717,000 persons, increasing substantially compared to 1998, the
Eurostat said.
</P>
<P>
Live births in the 15-nation EU were estimated at 4 million in
1999, which is 0.5 percent fewer than in 1998 and the lowest level
recorded since the Second World War.
</P>
<P>
Concerning births, the data available show a contrasting
picture of the EU member states: Luxemborg recorded the highest
annual growth rate with 4 percent, while Austria saw the sharpest
fall with -5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The natural increase of the population means that live births
minus deaths, according to the Eurostat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
