<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Norwegian Wins 10-kilometer World Cup Biathlon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Ole Einar Bjoerndalen of Norway,
Olympic gold medalist, Thursday overcame two shooting errors to
capture the men's 10-kilometer sprint title at a World Cup
biathlon competition in Oberhof, Germany.
</P>
<P>
Bjoerndalen, who missed the last three World Cup events last
month in Pokljuka, Slovenia to go home to train, powered to his
third victory this season in 25 minutes, 49.9 seconds and beat
Frank Luck of Germany by 7.9 seconds, despite two penalty laps for
the two missed targets.
</P>
<P>
Raphael Poiree of France was third, 11.6 seconds behind
Bjoerndalen, with one shooting error.
</P>
<P>
Sven Fischer of Germany, Luck's brother-in-law, retained his
lead in overall World Cup standings although he finished a distant
15th Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Fischer has 155 points, Luck is second with 138 and
Bjoerndalen is close behind with 136.
</P>
<P>
In addition to three first places, Bjoerndalen also has a
third and a fourth in his five starts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
