<HEADLINE> Highlights of Diplomatic News Today (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The following are the highlights
of diplomatic news released by Xinhua today.
</P>
<P>
State Councilor Meets ROK Guests
</P>
<P>
State Councilor Ismail Amat met today with Kim Ki-jai, minister
of government administration and local autonomy of the Republic of
Korea, and his party.
</P>
<P>
The ROK guests are here at the invitation of the Chinese
Ministry of Civil Affairs.
</P>
<P>
China Seriously Concerned about U. S. Arms Sale to Taiwan
</P>
<P>
China is seriously concerned about reports that U.S. President
Bill Clinton will approve large-scale sales of advanced weapons to
Taiwan out of the political consideration of the U.S. general
election, Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao said today.
</P>
<P>
Zhu told a press conference that the Chinese government and
people have always firmly opposed the sale of advanced weapons to
Taiwan by the U.S. government, and this stance is clear and
consistent.
</P>
<P>
He said that the U.S. government is obliged to honor its
commitment and act strictly in accordance with the Joint
Communique issued by the two governments on August 17, 1982, and
terminate immediately sales of advanced weapons to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the establishment of diplomatic relations
between the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) and Italy,
Zhu said that China welcomes this, and has supported the DPRK's
efforts to improve ties with the United States, Japan, the
European Union, and other Western countries, and to eventually
achieve the normalization of relations.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also announced that Vice-Premier Wu Bangguo will
pay a visit to the United Kingdom, Belgium, Switzerland, and the
European Union (EU) headquarters from January 18 to 31.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Wu will also attend an annual meeting of the World
Economic Forum in Davos, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
 Iraqi Deputy PM Arrives in Beijing
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz arrived in Beijing this
evening on a working visit to China.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Aziz's visit at a press conference earlier today,
Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao said that Chinese Vice-
President Hu Jintao, Vice-Premier Qian Qichen and Foreign Minister
Tang Jiaxuan will meet with Aziz respectively during his stay in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The two sides are expected to exchange views on bilateral
relations and international issues of common concern, he said. (
more)
</P>
</TEXT>
