<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Plans to Host Multilateral Mideast Peace Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov said here Thursday that Moscow plans to host a multi-
national Middle East peace conference next month, the first in more
than three years.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov, who is accompanying former Russian President Boris
Yeltsin on a three-day visit to the Holy Land to mark the first
Orthodox Christmas of the new millennium, said the conference would
be held at the level of foreign ministers.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported that a spokesman in the Israeli Foreign
Ministry confirmed the Russian plan. This may mark a comeback of
Russia to the stage of mideast peace-making - the former Soviet
Union was a co-sponsor of the mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
The multilateral peace negotiations will focus on key issues
concerning the entire Middle East region such as water,
environment, arms control, refugees and economic development.
</P>
<P>
The first multilateral negotiations were convened in Moscow in
January 1992 within the framework of a Mideast peace conference
held in the Spanish capital of Madrid in 1991, which kicked off the
Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
But the talks were frozen, together with the bilateral
negotiations, in early 1996 as the whole peace process came to a
halt following a series of terrorist attacks in Israel carried out
by Islamic militants.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin, who arrived in Israel Wednesday evening, attended a
ceremony at the Greek Orthodox Patriarchate Thursday to mark the
Orthodox Christmas. He and six Eastern European leaders were
named "Knights of the Holy Sepulcher." The Holy Sepulcher was the
church marking Jesus' burial place.
</P>
<P>
Later, Yeltsin had lunch with Israeli President Ezer Weizman. He
will also hold talks with Palestinian National Authority Chairman
Yasser Arafat in the Palestinian self-rule city of Bethlehem, the
birthplace of Jesus.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin shocked the world last Friday by announcing his
resignation from the presidency he had held since 1991. Prime
Minister Vladimir Putin was appointed acting president.
</P>
<P>
The visit to the Holy Land, which was planned when he was still
in office, was Yeltsin's first travel abroad since his resignation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
