<HEADLINE> Malaysian, British Firms in Joint Venture on Water Treatment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's Waste Water
Engineering Bhd (WWE) has entered into a joint venture agreement
with WRc Plc, a leading British international water management and
environment company, for sewage and water treatment.
</P>
<P>
The agreement finalized the terms of the joint venture and
facilitate the transfer of technology from WRc to WWE, as agreed
upon under a memorandum of understanding signed on June 18, 1999,
Bernama News Agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement established the respective parties' obligations
in relation to the joint venture by the formation of a research
and technical services company, in which WWE has 70 percent of the
stake and WRc 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, WRc will make available its expertise by
providing technical assistance in the provision of training to the
joint venture company's personnel.
</P>
<P>
It will also facilitate technology transfer and research and
development efforts in support of the venture and provide
expertise in the area of project planning, design implementation,
operation of plants, management and marketing.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture company is expected to establish a strong
position in the marketplace by developing its own product range of
process technologies with the appropriate technical consulting
skills in several areas of sewage and water treatment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
