<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Continue Downward Spiral </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market's
roller-coaster ride continued Thursday, with stocks ending a
volatile day's trading down after a late sell-off.
</P>
<P>
The share market began strongly despite Wednesday's large
losses. However, in the last hours of trade Thursday, the market
lost more than 30 points.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said local shares received a confidence boost early
following a rise on Wall Street overnight but further losses in
Asian markets and continued fears of interest rate rises resulted
in the late fall.
</P>
<P>
The All Ordinaries closed down 20.8 points to 3,030.1, after
hitting an intra-day high of 3,075.4 and a low of 3,026.
</P>
<P>
This follows Wednesday's 73.2-point fall, the largest single-
day decline in more than two years.
</P>
<P>
The All Industrials Index lost 39.4 points to 5,164.3 and the
All Resources Index was down 4.4 points to 1,399.5.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank, which hit a high of 22.3 Australian
dollars in intra-day trade, closed at 21.7 Australian dollars,
down 35 cents from Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth Bank finished 50 cents down to 24.85
Australian dollars, ANZ dropped 25.9 cents to 10.131 Australian
dollars and Westpac edged down 2 cents to 10.1 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was a volume of 755.13 million shares traded
for 1.36 billion Australian dollars (898 million U.S. dollars).
There were 761 rising stocks and 714 falling ones while 473
remained steady. 
</P>
</TEXT>
