<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Treasury Market Gets Record Revenue in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Singapore treasury markets
registered a record revenue of 4.8 billion Singapore dollars (2.86
billion U.S. dollars) in 1998, up 4.6 percent from the previous
year, according to the latest figures released Thursday by the
Singapore Foreign Exchange Market Committee (SFEMC).
</P>
<P>
SFEMC also said in its 1999 annual report that the total
treasury profits climbed by 7.1 percent to 3.3 billion Singapore
dollars (1.96 billion U.S. dollars) in the same period, the
largest total profits posted since the inception of the survey of
treasury activities in 1991.
</P>
<P>
SFEMC said it was of significance that direct costs fell by 5.7
percent under the weak price environment in 1998, the first time
it had fallen.
</P>
<P>
SFEMC has projected that 1999 would continue to be another good
year for treasury activities and affirmed that in the first half
of 1999 alone, banks in Singapore recorded revenues of 2.2 billion
Singapore dollars (1.3 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
According to the report, foreign exchange activities continued
to provide the largest revenue for treasury operation in Singapore,
contributing almost half of the total industry revenue, and money
market was the second largest revenue generator, contributing 35
percent to the total revenue.
</P>
<P>
SFEMC attributed the revenue increase in foreign exchange
activities to the increased volatility in financial markets in
1998, resulting in wider price spreads quoted for Asian and G7
currencies, as well as the higher premiums being placed on
liquidity.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, SFEMC noted that the number of treasury staff fell 5.
3 percent in 1998, in particular equity and money market dealers.
</P>
<P>
This was a reflection of the spate of consolidation activities
undertaken by banks during the Asian turmoil, it said.
</P>
<P>
However, SFEMC said, in line with the government's efforts to
promote Singapore as a leading debt origination and trading center,
the number of capital market professionals increased significantly
by 50 percent in 1998 compared with the previous year and average
revenue generated per dealer went up by 7.7 percent to 2.24
million Singapore dollars (1.33 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
SFEMC, launched in 1986, is a private-sector body of leading
treasury professionals and its purpose is to foster the growth of
Singapore as a leading international center for transactions in
foreign exchange and financial market instrument. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
