<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1,567 Filipinos Injured in Yuletide Revelries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government
reported Thursday that there were 1,567 cases of fireworks-related
injuries and 59 cases of stray bullets in the Yuletide revelries
across the country.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Health (DOH) said the figure was based on a
surveillance conducted by various government agencies between
December 21, 1999, and January 4, 2000, nationwide.
</P>
<P>
According to the DOH, most of the cases came from the national
capital region, which accounted for 56 percent or 882 cases of the
fireworks-related injuries and 59 percent or 35 cases of stray
bullets.
</P>
<P>
Based on the reports of DOH hospitals, which recorded 1,199
fireworks-related cases, there was a 41-percent increase compared
with the figure recorded in the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The age of the fireworks victims ranges between 5 months and 80
years old. The majority, or 86 percent, of the victims are male.
No casualty was reported in fireworks-related incidents.
</P>
<P>
The number of stray-bullet victims, on the other hand, is 18
percent higher compared with the figure a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The victims are between 3 and 57 years old and no casualty was
reported.
</P>
<P>
Health Secretary Alberto Romualdez said the increase in the
number of fireworks and stray bullet victims despite the
government's information campaign may have been due to the ardent
desire of the people to make a grand celebration for the new
millennium.
</P>
<P>
He promised that the department will implement more stringent
regulations on the manufacture, sale and use of fireworks and
pyrotechnic devices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
