<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spain's Jobless Rate Remains High Despite Sharp Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The unemployment rate in Spain
fell to a 20-year low of 9.7 percent in 1999, the first time since
1979 that it has been below 10 percent, data recently published by
the labor ministry showed.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1.61 million people were looking for a job in 1999,
172,000 or 9.6 percent less than in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a research report said that of the four million new
jobs created from 1994 to 1998 in Spain, Germany, France, Italy
and Britain, Spain represented 1.6 million, or 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
Analysts contributed the decline in unemployment to the fast
economic growth in Spain. The country registered a gross domestic
product growth of 3.7 percent in 1999, twice as much as the
average in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Structural reform favoring the development of communication,
service industry and infrastructure construction also helped
create new jobs.
</P>
<P>
In fact, since Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar formed his
government in 1996, 620,000 among the registered jobseekers have
found a new job. In 1999 in particular, more than 110, 000
thousand jobseekers benefited from the government-launched
training plan.
</P>
<P>
With an investment of 1,500 billion peseta (about 10 billion U.
S. dollars), the plan helped jobseekers to train for new job
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
However, Spain still faces problems in further reducing the
unemployment rate which despite a sharp decline still remains the
highest in the 15 European Union countries, analysts said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000106.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former French Interior Minister to Run for President in 2002 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Former French Interior Minister
and president of the Rally for France (RPF) party, Charles Pasqua,
has been designated by his party as its candidate for president in
the 2002 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
The National Bureau of the RPF said on Thursday that it fully
supports Pasqua's plan to run for president.
</P>
<P>
The RPF was created after the European Parliament election in
June 1999. The purpose of the party is to "protect France's
sovereignty in the face of globalization."
</P>
<P>
Pasqua, who was interior minister in the government of Edouard
Balladur in the early 1990s, is also the prefect of the 92nd
prefecture in the Parisian region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
