<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top 10 Chinese Scientific Discoveries in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Scholars of the Chinese Academy
of Sciences (CAS) and the Chinese Academy of Engineering (CAE)
have recently selected the top 10 Chinese scientific and
technological discoveries in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The successful launch of China's first experimental spacecraft
topped the list. The spacecraft "Shenzhou" was launched with a new
model of the "Long March" rocket on November 20 at the Jiuquan
Satellite Launch Center in northwest China's Gansu Province. "
Shenzhou" landed in the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region,
successfully completing its inaugural flight.
</P>
<P>
A major breakthrough in single-walled carbon nanotubes SWNT,
made by a research group from the Shenyang Metallic Institute of
CAS, came second.
</P>
<P>
Other major discoveries included heavy depletions in the ozone
layer on the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau; the finding of perhaps the
earliest vertebrate in the world; archaeological evidence for
dating the Xia (about 2100 B.C.-- 1600 B.C.) and Shang (1600 B.C. -
- 1100 B.C.) dynasties; China's first North Pole expedition; the
cultivation of a transgenetic cattle with human albumen genes; the
launch of China's first satellite for earth resources; the
successful cloning of Panda's embryo and the development of blood
substitutes.
</P>
<P>
The scholars also selected the top 10 scientific discoveries
worldwide during 1999. The deciphering of the complete genetic
sequence of chromosome 22 topped the list.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000106.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mideast Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey's state-run oil refinery, Tupras, will resume
full production by September 30, 2000, at the end of a
rehabilitation period following devastating earthquakes in western
Turkey in the second half of 1999, reported Turkish Daily News on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The quake damage at Tupras' Izmit refinery, the largest in
Turkey, was estimated at 115 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Tupras, the seventh largest oil refinery in Europe, meets 85
percent of Turkey's demand for petroleum products. Petroleum
accounts for 47 percent of the country's overall energy
consumption.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran has earned 15 million dollars from exports of
various types of flowers and ornamental plants since the beginning
of the current Iranian calendar year, which ends on March 20, head
of the Council of Flowers Producers Jalal Ajayebi said on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the Islamic Republic News Agency, Ajayebi said that
3,000 square meters of land is under flower cultivation in the
country which yields about 1 million stalks of flowers daily.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Managing Director of Iran Flowers and Ornamental
Plants Cooperative Reza Mehrabani said the Agriculture Ministry has
stipulated 200 million dollars worth of flowers and ornamental
plants exports by the end of the third five-year development plan
in 2005.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The World Bank, which has already pledged a three-
year, 3-billion-dollar loan to support Turkey's structural reforms,
has promised again to lend Turkey an extra 3 billion dollars, said
a statement issued by State Minister Recep Onal's office on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that World Bank President James Wolfensohn
had sent a letter to Onal last December 27 and assured Turkey of
the Bank's full support through supplying more funds.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- About 110,000 tons of various kinds of tires for
vehicles have been produced in the first three quarters of the
current Iranian calendar year.
</P>
<P>
The production showed a 4 percent increase compared to the same
period of last Iranian year.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel Aircraft Industries (IAI) has formulated its
new plan for 2000, under which the sales of the year will reach 2.
275 billion dollars, an increase of about 10 percent over 1999.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, IAI expects its pre-tax net profits to reach 105
million dollars by the end of 2000, an increase of about 50 percent
compared to the 70 million dollars in profit in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The 2000 operating budget also set aside 152 million dollars as
research and development expenditures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
