<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila to Continue With Labor-friendly Programs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government assured
the labor sector Thursday that it will continue "heightened"
efforts this year to create jobs and provide livelihood
opportunities and better working conditions for workers.
</P>
<P>
Secretary Bienvenido Laguesma of the Department of Labor and
Employment (DOLE) said these efforts include helping ensure
industrial peace to encourage more businesses to locate here.
</P>
<P>
"We continue with our job fairs to help people find jobs.
Government workers are also welcome to participate in these
activities to find better job opportunities," Laguesma said in a
radio interview.
</P>
<P>
He said there was greater industrial peace in 1999 compared to
1998, with strikes, lockouts and similar confrontations going down
by some 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
With brighter prospects for the economy in the year 2000, he
added, things would be even better this year for both laborers and
employers.
</P>
<P>
But Laguesma also called on both workers and employers to work
together to sustain industrial peace, saying this plays a crucial
role in attracting foreign investors to do business here, thus
opening up more opportunities for job seekers.
</P>
<P>
In a report submitted earlier to Philippine President Joseph
Estrada, the DOLE reported that in 1999, it mobilized the
commitment and cooperation of the different sectors in generating,
facilitating, enhancing and preserving employment.
</P>
<P>
Highlighting the DOLE's performance in 1999 was its job
facilitation program to help displaced workers, creating 644,717
jobs from July 1998 to September 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000106.0141 </DOCNO>
