<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Road Fatalities on Decline: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia is one of the best
among ASEAN countries in the area of road safety based on the
international-level indicator on fatal road accidents, according
to Transport Ministry Parliamentary Secretary Donald Lim Siang
Chai.
</P>
<P>
Based on the indicator, road fatalities in Malaysia have been
on the decline in recent years with the number of deaths for every
10,000 vehicles registered in 1998 declining from 8.4 in that year
to 5.7 in 1999, he said Thursday at a function here.
</P>
<P>
"Based on this rate also, Malaysia is one of the best among
developing countries and is on the same level with several
developed countries such as Belgium and Italy," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, road fatalities in Malaysia in 1996
totaled 6,304 compared with 6,302 in 1997 and 5,744 in 1998 while
between January and November 1999, there were 5,272 road deaths,
fewer than the corresponding period in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The decline in road fatalities since 1997 was in line with the
government target of 30 percent reduction in such deaths by the
year 2000, he said, adding that the government had attained a 15-
percent reduction in the rate of road deaths up to December 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
