<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Radar-Managed Aviation Zone in South China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The aviation fly zone in south
China, which encompasses civil routes for five major international
airports in Guangzhou and Macao and Hong Kong, has been brought
under the management control of a radar system.
</P>
<P>
This has helped shrink the distance between two flying
airliners from a criterion of 75 km to 10-20 km, and saves space
in the busiest aviation airspace in China with the highest daily
number of flights.
</P>
<P>
Sources with the Air Traffic Control department in Guangzhou
report that the new radar system, equipped with advanced data
processing devices, is capable of automatic management and is more
accurate than the old management system.
</P>
<P>
The radar facilities were built at a total cost of 313 million
yuan and are responsible for an averaged daily volume of 900
planes.
</P>
<P>
The China Civil Aviation Corp. will introduce the radar system
into three other artery air routes linking Beijing to Shanghai and
Guangzhou and Shanghai to Guangzhou in the second half of this
year, which accounts for 70 percent of the country's total air
traffic flow. 
</P>
</TEXT>
