<HEADLINE> Saddam: Embargo Has Started to be Corroded </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi President Saddam Hussein on
Thursday said that the United Nations embargo imposed on Iraq "has
actually started" to be corroded "thanks to the great fortitude and
the endurance of the Iraqi people."
</P>
<P>
Saddam made the remarks in a nationally televised address to
mark the 79th anniversary of the founding of the Iraqi National
Army.
</P>
<P>
He said "we have said it with certainty that the embargo will
not be lifted by a (U.N.) Security Council resolution, but will
corrode by itself."
</P>
<P>
Baghdad has long argued that it has carried out all its
commitments toward relevant U.N. resolutions, and demanded that the
Security Council lift the sanctions imposed on it since its 1990
invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
In his address, Saddam stopped short of rejecting directly a
latest U.N. resolution which calls for the return of U.N. arms
inspectors to Iraq in exchange for possible suspension of the U.N.
embargo.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has declared its rejection to the resolution, saying it
will not lead to the lifting, or even suspension of the sanctions,
rather it imposes new restrictions and conditions on Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
