<DOCNO> XIE20000106.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Aims to Lower Deficit in Year 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Israel's Finance Ministry has
promised to get the 2000 budget deficit down below 2.25 percent of
the gross national product (GNP), despite the cabinet's set target
of 2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said in a report available here Thursday that the
government's deficit in 1999, excluding net credit, totalled 9.2
billion shekels (2.19 billion U.S. dollars), or 2.3 percent of the
GNP.
</P>
<P>
This was 0.3 percent higher than the planned target, but still
lower than the deficit in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The figure was largely due to the government's domestic deficit,
which totaled 12.3 billion shekels (2.928 billion dollars). In its
overseas activities, the report said, the government had a surplus
of 3.1 billion shekels (0.73 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
According the report, both income and expenditure for 1999 were
below expectation, but revenues did pick up towards the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
Revenues in 1999 totaled 38.3 billion dollars, of which 34.09
billion dollars were from domestic activity and 4.21 billion from
overseas activity.
</P>
<P>
The deficit for 1999 was financed primarily by domestic loans
and the government's sales of bank shares and other privatizations.
</P>
<P>
The 2.5-percent target for 2000 was set half a year ago, when
the economy was still in stagnation and the anticipated economic
growth was only 3 percent, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Over the last year, the economy has revived and all signs
pointed to a growth of over 3 percent this year while revenues will
grow substantially, it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
