<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Foreign Investment Drops Sharply in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's approved foreign
investment in 1999, including the joint ventures, decreased to
592 million U.S. dollars from the previous year's 1.58 billion
U.S. dollars, the Business weekly reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Figures provided by the Zimbabwe Investment Center showed that
during 1999, most of the foreign investment was in manufacturing
followed by commercial, mining, tourism and construction.
</P>
<P>
A combination of high inflation and interests rates, negative
publicity and conflicting policy statements had prevented the
country from getting any meaningful investment last year, th
center said.
</P>
<P>
Nick Ncube, Executive Director of the center, admitted that
last year was a difficult year. However, he is optimistic about
this year's prospects which he said would be driven by a number of
new developments initiated last year.
</P>
<P>
The government has increased the rate of subcontracting of
entities to the private sector as part of its efforts to boost
investment this year, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
