<DOCNO> XIE20000106.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Agencies Issue Year 2000 Appeal to Eradicate Polio  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization (
WHO) and the United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF) have jointly
called on leaders of 30 affected nations to give full cooperation
to the global effort to eradicate polio by the end of the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
"We are on the verge of an historic public health victory, the
eradication of poliomyelitis, a disease that has caused untold
suffering to millions of children in all parts of the world," said
WHO Director-General Gro Harlem Brundtland and UNICEF Executive
Director Carol Bellamy in a New Year's letter published here
Thursday to 30 heads of state in sub-Saharan Africa and South Asia.
</P>
<P>
Launched in 1988, the global initiative to eradicate polio by
the end of the year 2000 is spearheaded by WHO, Rotary
International, UNICEF and the U.N. Foundation.
</P>
<P>
To win the battle against the disease, Brundtland and Bellamy
urged them to provide leadership for extra immunization activities,
to allocate sufficient resources to support National Immunization
Days and routine immunization and surveillance activities, to
mobilize support for these efforts at the national to the
community level and to facilitate truces in areas affected by
conflict.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders of the two agencies cited the significant
achievements since the launch of the initiative in 1988:
</P>
<P>
-- The number of polio cases has fallen from an estimated 350,
000 in 1998 to some 5,200 reported cases in 1999;
</P>
<P>
-- The proportion of the world's children living in polio-
infected areas has dropped from 90 percent to less than 50 percent;
</P>
<P>
-- Polio has been eradicated from the Americans, Europe, the
countries of the Western Pacific, and much of the Middle East and
has disappeared from most of northern and southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
According to WHO, the world will save 1.5 billion U.S. dollars
per year with the eradication of polio and the eventual cessation
of polio immunization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
