<HEADLINE> Japan's Top Police Chief Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Japan's National Police Agency (
NPA) chief Yuko Sekiguchi Thursday announced he will step down as
the country's top police officer.
</P>
<P>
In announcing his resignation, Sekiguchi denied speculation
that he is resigning to take the responsibility for a series of
scandals that hit Kanagawa prefecture police last year.
</P>
<P>
"The scandals were regrettable, but we have set the course for
creating ways to prevent similar incidents. I am not resigning to
take the blame," Sekiguchi told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
The 60-year-old senior police officer said he thought it "
appropriate" to quit after holding the post for nearly three years,
having finished working out primary security measures for the
summit of the Group of Eight nations to be held in Okinawa in July
as well as a plan to prevent police misconduct.
</P>
<P>
Sekiguchi had come under fire for a spate of scandals involving
police officers in Kanagawa Prefecture, south of Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
The incidents, which came to light in the latter half of last
year, included a cover-up of a police officer's drug use, sexual
harassment, attempted extortion, violence, bullying within the
force, and a hit-and-run case.
</P>
<P>
Setsuo Tanaka, the NPA's deputy director general, has been
tipped to succeed Sekiguchi after Japan's National Public Safety
Commission officially announces his resignation with the approval
of Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi and cabinet ministers next Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
