establishment of a commission to probe the environmental situation
in the Bosphorus Straits, the Marmara and Black seas after a
Russian tanker ran aground and leaked huge amount of oil in the
Marmara sea, leading to a potential environmental disaster.
</P>
<P>
Some agencies have blamed the accident on negligent
administration of authorities in Istanbul, the largest city in
Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000106.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodian Cabinet Approves Draft Law of KR Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Cambodian cabinet, after
more than four hours of debate, approved a draft law on Thursday
on setting up Extraordinary Chambers to try former Khmer Rouge
leaders.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Hun Sen presided over the meeting of the Council
of Ministers.
</P>
<P>
The draft law will then be immediately sent to the National
Assembly and the Senate for final passage.
</P>
<P>
Cabinet Minister Sok An told reporters that ministers supported
the draft law, adding that since the draft law was completed in
late December, "we have considered the points put forward by the U.
N. Secretary-General and made some revisions."
</P>
<P>
Sok An said the interested countries including the United
States, France and Russia have also expressed their satisfaction
with the draft law. Legal experts from France, Russia and India
took part the drafting of the law.
</P>
<P>
The Council of Ministers said in late December that the
government needed more discussion with the United Nations on how
to conduct the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
The draft law contains provisions for the establishment of the
Extraordinary Chambers based on Phnom Penh's existing Trial,
Appeals and Supreme Courts.
</P>
<P>
On the expenses of the Extraordinary Chambers, the revised
draft law sets out that the government shall meet the costs of
Cambodian judges, while countries providing judges would be asked
to meet their own costs.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen insisted that the trial should not be internationalized
or based on the United Nation's finances.
</P>
<P>
Each level of the courts will have a Cambodian majority, but to
reach a verdict will require a "super-majority" of votes, which
means that at least one foreign judge is needed.
</P>
<P>
The term for the judges and co-prosecutors is four years and
the trials' judges would be appointed by the Supreme Council of
the Magistracy while the foreign judges are to be appointed as
requested by the U.N. Secretary General following consultation of
the Royal Government of Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
The draft law also outlines that if foreign judges or
prosecutors chosen by the U.N. or other countries do not
participate in the Extraordinary Chambers, Cambodian judges or
prosecutors would be chosen to replace them.
</P>
<P>
The charges against the accused include genocide, crimes
against humanity, destruction of cultural property and crimes
against internationally protected persons.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen said earlier that the focus of the trial could be
narrowed to only four to five of the former Khmer Rouge leaders,
and Ieng Sary, the former Khmer Rouge foreign minister, would not
be among them. Ieng Sary defected with several thousand guerrillas
to the royal government and was later pardoned by King Norodom
Sihanouk for his 1979 death sentence.
</P>
<P>
Only two former Khmer Rouge leaders -- military commander Ta
Mok and the former Tuol Sleng security chief known as Duch -- are
currently in jail in Phnom Penh.
</P>
<P>
The maximum sentence for those found guilty will range from a
minimum of five years in prison to life imprisonment and seizure
of assets.
</P>
<P>
The Cambodian government has rejected an international tribunal
abroad or a joint-U.N. tribunal, insisting that the country's
sovereignty be preserved over the process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
