<HEADLINE> Leading Chinese Exporter Starts Operation in Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 6 (Xinhua) -- A 100,000-spindle cotton mill
financed by the China Huayuan Group, a major exporter in Shanghai,
will become operational in Sonora State, Mexico, this year.
</P>
<P>
The plant, with a total investment of 96 million U.S. dollars,
is the largest project ever funded by China in a foreign country.
</P>
<P>
All production lines and related technology, worth some 44
million U.S. dollars, will be provided by Chinese suppliers.
</P>
<P>
Established in 1992, the China Huayuan Group is a leading
exporter of machinery, textiles and electronics products. Its
export income, which has been increasing at a double-digit rate
annually, reached 266 million U.S. dollars in 1998, ranking fourth
in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The group has operations in Niger, Uganda, and Tadzhikistan,
and aims to establish 10 more production centers and 20 trade
companies abroad over the next five years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
