<DOCNO> XIE20000106.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Imports to Top 1.3 Trillion Dollars Over 6 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 6 (Xinhua) -- China's total imports will
exceed 1.3 trillion U.S. dollars from 2000 through 2005,
representing an annual growth of over eight percent, said minister
of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation Shi Guangsheng here
today.
</P>
<P>
Shi told Xinhua that China will realize its great potential as
the country's modernization drive continues its momentum.
</P>
<P>
Since the founding of New China in 1949, and especially since
China began its reform and opening up program in 1979, the country
's economy has sustained rapid growth, with the living standards
of the Chinese people improved, the domestic investment and
consumption market continuously expanded, and foreign trade
invigorated. Imports grew to 165 billion U.S. dollars in 1999.
</P>
<P>
As the Chinese government continues to pursue an active fiscal
policy by issuing more treasury bonds this year, investment from
the state coffer will focus on infrastructure construction and
technological upgrading of enterprises in order to accelerate
economic restructuring, stimulate investment by non-government
sectors, and jump-start consumption. The growth rate of the
economy is predicted at around seven percent this year.
</P>
<P>
Shi said that in the medium-and long run, China's economy will
be able to sustain a rapid growth rate as it continues to place
emphasis on developing such fields as water conservancy, energy,
transport, telecommunications, raw materials, environmental
protection, and high technology. Those are areas slated by the
central government as priorities.
</P>
<P>
China will encourage imports with appropriate measures,
especially increasing the introduction of new and advanced
technologies and key equipment. This will provide huge trade and
investment opportunities for overseas businesspeople.
</P>
<P>
Economic growth and accession to the World Trade Organization (
WTO) require that China further expand the areas open to the
overseas firms. Step by step, the nation will give overseas
investors access to the sectors of finance, insurance, foreign
trade, retailing, and tourism.
</P>
<P>
China will give green light to overseas investors who want to
set up joint ventures, cooperative projects and wholly-owned
enterprises in these areas, Shi said. This is both an important
move toward participating in the integration of the world economy
and a great impetus to the introduction of foreign funds, advanced
technology and equipment, and managerial expertise.
</P>
<P>
Noted economist Hu Angang said that China has great potential
for trade surplus and import growth. After joining the WTO, the
country is expected to further lower its tariff rates and turn the
present approval system for imports into a registration system.
</P>
<P>
China now ranks tenth in the world in import volume, and Hu
predicted that by 2005, China will become the fifth-largest
importer in the world.
</P>
<P>
At present, the country maintains a sound foreign exchange
reserve, which serves as a strong support for the expansion of
imports. By the end of 1999, the country had a total foreign
exchange reserve of 154.6 billion U.S. dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000106.0180 </DOCNO>
