<DOCNO> XIE20000106.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian External Debt Down by 6.2 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The total external debt of
Tanzania decreased by 6.2 percent by the end of November last year
to 7,296.3 million U.S. dollars from 7,778.6 million U.S. dollars
registered in October.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest issue of the Monthly Economic Review of
the Bank of Tanzania, out of the total amount disbursed, the
outstanding debt of the country stood at 6,158.6 million U.S.
dollars, while committed undisbursed debt was 1,137.7 million U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Multilateral and bilateral debts contributed the largest share
of the country's total debt, accounting for 56.9 percent and 35.3
percent respectively, the document said.
</P>
<P>
According to the monthly review, agriculture, energy and mining
sectors received 16.5 percent and 14 percent of the debt
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Industries absorbed 7.2 percent of the total debt while social
welfare and education, finance and insurance, and tourism received
five percent, 3. 9 percent and 1.3 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The remaining 12.5 percent was absorbed by other sectors.
</P>
<P>
During the month under review, the country's domestic debt
declined by 8. 7 billion Tanzanian shillings (about 11 million
U.S. dollars) due to government repayment of principal and
interest securities.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the document said Tanzania's export earnings from
traditional commodities during last November increased by 152.8
percent from last October to 64.2 million U.S. dollars while
receipts from non-traditional commodities declined by 39.4 percent
to 21.2 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
This is attributed to higher export volumes for such
traditional commodities as coffee, cotton, sisal, tea, tobacco and
cashew nuts, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000106.0196 </DOCNO>
