<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Gives Priority to Developing Key Rural Towns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 6 (Xinhua) -- China is set to develop around
10,000 key rural towns early this century in order to raise the
social and economic development of rural areas to a new level.
</P>
<P>
A senior official with the Ministry of Construction said today
that China had developed more than 55,000 small rural towns by the
end of 1999, which are home to 70,000 specialized and wholesale
markets with accumulative annual trade volume of more than 500
billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Small rural towns account for approximately 25 percent of China
's total gross domestic product and are rapidly emerging as
important bases for boosting rural economic development, the
official added.
</P>
<P>
He noted that township enterprises in these towns employ over
150 million farmers and contribute over 70 percent to the country'
s total rural output value.
</P>
<P>
Township employers will be able to hire an average of seven to
eight million rural laborers annually in the coming years, he said,
adding that the rapidly increasing number of small towns will not
only help absorb large numbers of surplus rural laborers, but will
also stimulate efforts to restructure agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that some 60 percent of the country's 20
million township enterprises are concentrated in small rural towns,
and that a large number of enterprise groups in developed rural
towns have annual output values of over one billion yuan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000106.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Student Expelled for Assault of Woman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Dhaka University authorities on
Wednesday expelled a student for his alleged involvement in the
assault of a woman during the New Year Millennium night
celebrations, newspapers here reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Acting Vice Chancellor Professor Shahadat Ali ordered the
expulsion in conformity with the recommendations of a campus facts-
finding committee, which found Alias Russell of the university's
Botany Department guilty of assaulting the young woman along with
others, on the basis of primary evidences.
</P>
<P>
The authorities have requested the law enforcing agencies to
arrest and take legal actions against Russell.
</P>
<P>
A group of youths, reportedly drunk, stripped the girl of her
clothes on December 31 night on the campus as she came with her
brother to join the New Year's celebrations.
</P>
<P>
Ali termed the incident "barbaric" and said the university
authorities would be more careful in future.
</P>
<P>
He said volunteers will be deployed on the campus on the eve of
future festivals as part of the university's own security measures
to resist any "untoward" incident.
</P>
<P>
The incident created strong resentment in society. Denouncing
the incident, the Bangladesh Women's Association staged
demonstrations in the city streets Tuesday. Leaders of the
association demanded exemplary punishment of the youths
responsible for such "heinous acts."
</P>
<P>
Students of Dhaka University Tuesday burnt some of the dailies
for publishing photograph of the girl who was subjected to assault.
"The photo of the culprits instead of the victims should be
published in the mass media," the angry protesters demanded.
</P>
<P>
The government has already directed the law enforcing agencies
to detect the culprits and take legal steps against them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
