<HEADLINE> Thai Govt's Shareholding in Thai Airways to Be Cut down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Thai Airways International (THAI)
is trying to reduce the share holdings of the Thai government in
it to less than 70 percent from 93 percent, a senior official of
the national carrier said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Dararatana Masakanok, manager of Equity Department, told Xinhua
that THAI will sell about 300 million shares to public or a new
strategic partner in order to raise new capital, but it is not
decided yet.
</P>
<P>
"The decision will be made in the near future", she said.
</P>
<P>
However, any plan would need final approval from the Thai
cabinet before the sale could go ahead.
</P>
<P>
Dararatana denied the reports that the airline will sell 400
million shares this year, saying the reports were "rumors."
</P>
<P>
The airline first announced a plan to issue new shares to raise
fresh capital last June, with the aim of cutting the Finance
Ministry's holding as a first step towards privatization.
</P>
<P>
Privatization of some state enterprises is a key to the Thai
government's economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
The ministry holds 1.3 billion shares, or a 93 percent stake,
in THAI.
</P>
<P>
Some foreign airlines, including Singapore Airlines, have shown
interest in bidding for a share in the Thai carrier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
