<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Horticulture Export Earnings Soar in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's horticulture industry,
the country's fastest growing agricultural sector, continued to
experience rapid growth in 1999, earning 100 million U.S. dollars
in exports last year during the marketing season, the Business
weekly reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
This was through the export of 26,072 tons of flowers and fresh
produce.
</P>
<P>
The sector had earned 58 million U.S. dollars in same period
the previous year from the export of 25,000 tons of flowers,
vegetables and fruits.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Business on Wednesday, Chief Executive
of the Horticultural Promotion Council Stanley Heri said the
performance of the sector is still restrained by punitive tariffs,
which have held back expansion, especially the acquisition of
hi-tech greenhouses.
</P>
<P>
Small-scale growers have been the hardest hit, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Heri, the lack of appropriate infrastructure,
especially post harvest handling facilities, poor roads and
communication network and the lack of appropriate technical skills
to grow export crops have stifled small players in the sector.
</P>
<P>
Horticulture is the country's third largest agricultural
commodity after tobacco and livestock and the second largest
foreign exchange earner after tobacco.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that the world trade in horticulture produce
would continue to increase, Heri said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
