<DOCNO> XIE20000106.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Expert: World's Longest Canal Can Be Clear Again (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
So far, Zhejiang Province alone is in the process of
constructing 20 sewage disposal projects along the river, which
are expected to be completed in three to five years. These
facilities are expected to completely purify local industrial
waste water and that from local residents who discharge into the
waterway, according to Kong.
</P>
<P>
Enterprises situated along the river which were once reluctant
to pay for waste treatment are now willing to do so, as required
for enterprises seeking bank loans.
</P>
<P>
A proposal has been approved to connect the canal with one that
runs from Hangzhou to Ningbo, a coastal city in Zhejiang Province,
thereby making it possible for polluted water from the Beijing-
Hangzhou canal to be diluted, to some extent, by the water of the
Qiantangjiang River.
</P>
<P>
Pollution from the agricultural sector also must be taken into
consideration, said Kong, because 40 percent of the fertilizers
used on nearby farmland goes into the canal. So, Kong has
suggested that farmers use smaller amounts and more pollution-free
fertilizers.
</P>
<P>
All these efforts are expected to return clarity to the
waterway, which long ago was used as a daily water source by the
people living along the canal.
</P>
<P>
The endeavor to control pollution in the canal will certainly
pay off, and add to the attractiveness of many small towns in
Zhejiang and Jiangsu provinces through which the waterway flows.
</P>
<P>
These cities situated on the centuries-old canal are among the
nation's most popular tourist destinations for their rich cultural
legacies and delicate traditional features such as gardens,
temples, bridges, and pavilions. These cities include Hangzhou and
Suzhou, two of the country's most famous scenic spots, often
compared to Heaven on Earth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
