<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China Province Sets High Growth Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, January 6 (Xinhua) -- East China's Jiangsu Province,
which ranks second in the country in terms of Gross Domestic
Product (GDP), has set its growth target at 10 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
Chen Huanyou, secretary of the Jiangsu Provincial Committee of
the Communist Party of China, said that this goal is obtainable as
the local economy has maintained a healthy growth momentum over
the past few years, with the 1999 GDP reaching 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
To achieve this year's goal, Chen said, the province will
further enhance investment to spur domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
About 60 key construction projects will be launched, including
two bridges across the Yangtze River and a subway in Nanjing, the
provincial capital.
</P>
<P>
At least 100 billion yuan will be spent for the technological
upgrading of major industries, according to Chen.
</P>
<P>
Priority will be given to creating a number of large enterprise
groups, each with annual sales of more than 10 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Private enterprises are encouraged to engage in infrastructure
construction and the upgrading of state-owned enterprises, Chen
said.
</P>
<P>
Greater efforts also will be made to explore new consumption
areas, such as education, tourism, and housing, Chen added.
</P>
<P>
China's national economy is expected to grow around seven
percent in 2000, according to officials from the State Development
Planning Commission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
