<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Now a Cleaner City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 6 (Xinhua) -- This leading industrial and
commercial city in China has become more beautiful and its water
purer.
</P>
<P>
The second phase of the city's Treatment Project for Polluted
Water was completed recently, reducing more than one million tons
of polluted water daily.
</P>
<P>
In the project's second phase, waste water from Minhang, Wujing
and Huangpu districts and Pudong New Area, covering a combined
area of 272 square kilometers, is now purified before flowing into
the Huangpu River, with the waste water carried through 130
kilometers of pipes.
</P>
<P>
Work on this second phase began in June 1997 with an investment
of 6.3 billion yuan (759 million U.S. dollars), including 285
million U.S. dollars in World Bank loans.
</P>
<P>
The 1.6 billion-yuan first phase of the project was completed
in the early 1990s, reducing 1.4 million tons of polluted water
daily. Shanghai now is making plans for the third-phase of the
project.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
