<DOCNO> XIE20000106.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Expert: World's Longest Canal Can Be Clear Again (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Environmental protection expert
Kong Shu has great confidence that the sight of a variety of fish
swimming and shrimp wandering along the once-limpid Beijing-
Hangzhou Great Canal that he remembers from his childhood will
once again become a reality in a few years.
</P>
<P>
Kong believes that the 1,789-km-long canal, the longest in the
world, can become clear again in three to five years because he is
encouraged by the growing attention now given to the treatment of
pollution on the waterway which is caused by advanced
industrialization along the river.
</P>
<P>
Kong Shu is vice director of the institute of design and
research for environmental protection in east China's Zhejiang
Province.
</P>
<P>
The nearly 1,400-year-old canal winds southward from Beijing
through the city of Tianjin and Shandong Province, down to Anhui
and Jiangsu provinces, and ends in Hangzhou, the capital of
Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
The canal plays an important role in the country's economic
growth as its transport capacity is four times that of the
parallel Beijing-Shanghai railway line.
</P>
<P>
But the canal's handling capacity has been hampered by
distorted navigation routes, shallow water, and low bridges in
recent years, and only the section south of Shandong Province is
now able to accommodate water traffic.
</P>
<P>
What is worse, the canal, once with clear water from surface to
bottom, is now seriously polluted, causing people walking
alongside it to cover their nose and mouth from the foul and
disgusting stench of polluted water, a result of the mushrooming
and speedy development of township industrial enterprises along
the river, especially in Jiangsu and Zhejiang provinces, since the
1980s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000106.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Launch Master Plan for Industrial  Revolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka is to launch a master
plan for the period 2000-2010 with the help of foreign and local
experts to usher in an industrial revolution, the Ministry of
Industrial Development said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The master plan, due to be finalized in July this year, will be
used in compiling the "White Paper on Industrialization," said a
ministry statement.
</P>
<P>
The stage one of the master plan has been completed and six
sectors have been identified for detailed study as "target
industries" by the Japan International Cooperation Agency (JICA)
and United Nations Industrial Development Organization (UNIDO),
said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The interim recommendation of the ministry and the Japanese
experts is to promote industrialization in a selective and
strategic manner through the promotion of target industries.
</P>
<P>
The target industries have been classified as globally-linked
industries such as apparel, leather and rubber and policy-driven
industries such as electric or electronic, plastic, machinery and
information technology.
</P>
<P>
Globally-linked industries will be promoted through
competitiveness in the world market. Policy-driven industries will
be developed strategically to serve as basic industries and
support other categories of industries.
</P>
<P>
An international workshop planned for later this month with the
participation of experts from Singapore, Malaysia, Japan and India
is expected to produce a new industrialization policy to
operationalize the new strategy of globalization.
</P>
<P>
The UNIDO is expected to develop, coordinate and actively
support industrial development in Sri Lanka for which a budget of
16 million U.S. dollars has been allocated.
</P>
<P>
The UNIDO intervention will complement JICA assistance and help
formulate a new industrial policy, said the statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
