<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liver Donator Honored in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 6 (Xinhua) -- A Malaysian was Thursday
honored with the Guinness Effort Award (GEA) for donating part of
his liver to a boy called Mohamed Afiq Iqmal in the country's
first successful transplantation involving organs from a live and
non-related person.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Deputy Health Minister Suleiman Mohamed presented the
award to Wan Hafizam Wan Ismail, 23 years old, whose noble deed
earned him a GEA certificate, a personalized goblet and a special
gift of his choice -- a home theater set.
</P>
<P>
The GEA was incepted in July 1975 as part of Guinness Anchor
Berhad's community relations program with the objective to foster
a sense of national pride and civic consciousness among Malaysians
by recognizing commendable achievements or deeds that could stand
as an example for others to emulate.
</P>
<P>
The recipient is selected by an independent panel of judges
comprising senior representatives from leading news agencies in
Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Hafizam was selected in recognition of his noble and selfless
act in donating part of his liver to Mohamed Afiq who was 15
months old at the time of the operation last April, according to
GEA panel Chairman K. Nayagam.
</P>
<P>
Mohamed Afiq celebrated his second birthday Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The boy suffered serious liver problem since he was nine months
old after the duct connecting his liver to the intestine was
blocked,giving rise to complications which needed the organ
transplant.
</P>
<P>
His sufferings attracted public attention and Wan Hafizam,
unknown to Mohamed Afiq's family, offered his liver. 
</P>
</TEXT>
