<DOCNO> XIE20000106.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nicaraguan FM Says Normalization of Ties With Honduras Possible </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Nicaraguan Minister of Foreign
Relations Eduardo Montealegre said Wednesday that it would be
possible for Nicaragua and Honduras to sign an accord for the
normalization of their relations.
</P>
<P>
Nicaragua's relations with its northern neighbor worsened after
Honduras ratified with Colombia the 1986 Maritime Delimitation
Treaty, which according to the Nicaragua government, takes away
from it 130,000 square kilometers of continental platform.
</P>
<P>
"This (the signing of a bilateral accord) is possible, but no
date has been set," said Montealegre
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, these possibilities will depend on the results of
the Washington meeting, programmed for January 12 and 13 at the
Organization of American States (OAS) headquarters, he said.
</P>
<P>
"I consider there may still be lacking three or four further
meetings," indicated the head of Nicaragua's diplomacy.
Montealegre said that the Washington meeting will be made to
define a zone of military exclusion in the Caribbean sea and
establish mechanisms for international verification.
</P>
<P>
The meeting between Montealegre and his Honduran counterpart
Roberto Flores Bermudez is the continuation of negotiations that
began December 29 and 30, 1999, in Miami, the United States, in
the presence of OAS special envoy Luigi Einaudi.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, the ministers from both Central American
countries agreed the immediate separation of military forces at
the common border and the establishment of a military exclusion
zone in the Caribbean sea.
</P>
<P>
They also committed themselves in Miami to freezing military
posts and personnel on the border area. Under the OAS mediation,
ministers of both countries carried through in Miami an initial
negotiation.
</P>
<P>
According to reports coming from Honduras, Minister Flores also
declared presidents Arnoldo Aleman and Carlos Flores, of Nicaragua
and Honduras respectively, may sign a bilateral accord this month.
He said it is probable that negotiations in Washington allow
sufficient advance so that the presidents of both countries can
sign a document. 
</P>
</TEXT>
