<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Military to Make All-out Effort to End Violence in Maluku </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Military (TNI)
Commander Admiral Widodo vowed on Wednesday to make an all-out
effort to end the long standing religious conflicts in Maluku.
</P>
<P>
He said that TNI is ready to send more troops to the region if
it is really necessary, but said that so far the number of troops
deployed in Maluku has been adequate.
</P>
<P>
Widodo revealed that 12 battalions (12,000 troops) have been
deployed in Maluku, with three battalions from local military
headquarters and nine battalions sent from other regions.
</P>
<P>
He said the TNI would do its utmost to settle all the unrest in
the east Indonesian region and not hesitate to disarm the
conflicting parties.
</P>
<P>
"And if need be, we will impose a curfew," he was quoted by
national newspapers Thursday as saying.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with Ambon Catholic Bishop Petrus Mandagi on
Wednesday, President Abdurrahman Wahid said he ordered the
military to take tougher measures to stop the violence.
</P>
<P>
"The president was very saddened by the ongoing violence in
Maluku, and he promised to take all necessary measures to end the
tragic events," Mandagi was quoted by the Jakarta Post Thursday as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Coordinating Minister for Political Affairs and
Security Gen. Wiranto disclosed that the government may soon
isolate Maluku, including from media coverage, to prevent outside
influences which could foment the violence.
</P>
<P>
"After the situation calms down, we will isolate the region.
This does not mean that the region is closed, but we hope that the
isolation will help to avoid biased reports about Maluku," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Home Affairs Minister Suryadi Soedirdja said the communal
clashes in Maluku had become a "human tragedy" in which the
conflicting sides appeared bent on exterminating each other.
</P>
<P>
He said he fully supported the TNI's willingness to do all
within its power to restore peace and security there.
</P>
<P>
Brutal conflicts in Maluku have been taking place for more than
12 months and have seen almost 2,000 Muslims and Christians
slaughtered.
</P>
<P>
Pattimura Military Commander Brig. Gen. Max Tamaela said in
Ambon, capital of Maluku, that the situation had calmed down on
Wednesday with only sporadic reports of violence.
</P>
<P>
"The forces deployed have succeeded in establishing a barrier
between the two parties," he said.
</P>
<P>
Tamaela called on all parties to remain calm but conceded that
the level of animosity was high. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
