<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke010610 Indonesian Govt to Review Discriminative Laws Against Ethnic Chinese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government has
pledged to review all discriminative laws, regulations and native
policies against the ethnic Chinese in the country.
</P>
<P>
Coordinating Minister for Political and Security Affairs Gen.
Wiranto said at least 13 government regulations and one
presidential decree will be reviewed following a recent pledge
made by President Abdurrahman Wahid to eliminate discrimination
against the ethnic Chinese and other minorities.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Home Affairs Surjadi Soedirja and Minister of Law
and Legislation Yusril Mahendra have been assigned to study the
technical aspects of the policies, leading newspapers Thursday
quoted the minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
The laws and regulations which will be revoked include those on
culture, economics, religion and various civil rights, Wiranto
said Wednesday after attending a cabinet meeting chaired by
President Adburrahman Wahid at the Bina Graha presidential office.
</P>
<P>
In the time of former president Soeharto, it was illegal to
teach the Chinese language in schools and Chinese publications
were banned in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Under the discriminative policy, the ethnic Chinese, which make
up about 5 percent of Indonesia's population of 210 million or the
third largest populous nationality in the country, have been a
target for popular resentment and their shops and houses have
regularly been attacked in periods of unrest.
</P>
<P>
The worst incident in recent years occurred in May 1998 before
the downfall of Soeharto during which rioters conducted attacks on
ethnic Chinese, burned down their shops, schools, houses and
churches, claiming about 1,200 lives. The rioters also conducted
wide-spread rape and torture on ethnic Chinese women.
</P>
<P>
President Abdurrahman Wahid has frequently condemned violence
and discriminative actions, pointing out that his new government
will not allow any kind of discriminative actions against any
minorities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
