<HEADLINE> Thailand's Domestic Airports to Install X-Ray  to Stop Trafficking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's domestic airports
will be installed with x-ray equipment to scan all luggage and
boxes loaded on planes as part of a new purge on drug trafficking,
Bangkok Post reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Commissioner of the Narcotics Suppression Bureau of Thailand
Komkrich Patpongpanich was quoted as saying on Wednesday that
narcotics police were on full alert for an expected increase in
activity by traffickers moving drugs from the North to the Central
region, particularly Bangkok and its surrounding provinces.
</P>
<P>
Checkpoints were being set up on key roads in the northwest and
northeast and suspicious vehicles were being checked, he added.
</P>
<P>
The move follows Monday's seizure of 2.6 million
methamphetamine pills in Central province of Nonthaburi.
</P>
<P>
Komkrich said police had information that the pills came from
the northern provinces.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister's Office Minister Jurin Laksanavisit also
announced measures to combat the increasing use of aircraft and
vessels for drug smuggling.
</P>
<P>
He had asked the Narcotics Control Board, Thai Airways
International, the Airports Authority of Thailand and other
agencies to be strict in monitoring shipping and air cargo.
</P>
<P>
A total of 45 million methamphetamine tablets were seized, 170,
000 drug suspects arrested, and assets valued at 190 million baht
(about 5 million U.S.dollars) were seized in Thailand last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
