<HEADLINE> Gore, Bradley Accuse Each Other in Fourth Debate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 5 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Democratic presidential
front-runner Al Gore and Bill Bradley, his rival for the party's
presidential nomination, mounted their attacks against each other
as the election campaign heated up after the Christmas and new
year holidays.
</P>
<P>
In a one-hour debate at a university in New Hampshire State on
Wednesday night, Bradley, a former senator in New Jersey, accused
vice president Al Gore of deliberately distorting his proposal to
expand health coverage.
</P>
<P>
Bradley said the vice president "offended me" by claiming he
would hurt African-Americans and Latinos and by saying his health
care plan would shortchange many Americans.
</P>
<P>
In response, Gore shot back that his rival's plan would leave
many New Hampshire residents "high and dry."
</P>
<P>
The debate was the fourth between the two rivals and also the
first in the election year.
</P>
<P>
The former senator launched a sharp attack on the Clinton-Gore
administration's handling of relations with Russia, saying the
United States had not pushed hard enough in the last eight years
to reduce the stockpile of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
"I think that in spite of the problems there have been some
successes, including a new leader committed to reform, a free
press and free elections," Gore defended.
</P>
<P>
The exchange of attacks came one-third of the way through the
debate, the first in a series of confrontations in which Democrats
and Republicans will take turns debating in the run-up to the
first balloting of the presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
Bradley, who is even or ahead in the polling in advance of the
nation's first primary set for February 1 in New Hampshire, has
mounted a strong challenge in the state against Vice President
Gore.
</P>
<P>
The two rivals clashed on most issues, but they agreed on some
issues such as a need for stricter gun control laws and appointing
a Joint Chief of Staff who would support policy of permitting gays
to serve openly in the military. 
</P>
</TEXT>
