<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bank Indonesia Predicts 3-4 Pct Growth for 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Bank Indonesia has predicted
that the country's economy in the year 2000 will enjoy a growth of
three to four percent.
</P>
<P>
Bank Indonesia attributes the good economic prospects to
improving domestic and international economic development.
</P>
<P>
"On the whole, the improving international economy will provide
a climate conducive to domestic economic growth," Bank Indonesia
Governor Syahril Sabirin was quoted by national newspapers
Thursday as saying.
</P>
<P>
From the supply point of view, Sabirin said, all sectors were
predicted to improve and register a positive growth, while from
the demand point of view, domestic consumption would continue to
increase due to increasing income, recovery of consumers'
confidence and relatively stable prices.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Bank Indonesia will also continue its policy
of keeping interest rates low to help revive the banking industry
and also the real sector, which will thus stimulate economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia is emerging from its worst recession in decades. The
economy shrank by 13.7 percent and inflation topped 80 percent in
1998. The country's output was little changed in 1999, with
inflation slowing to 2.01 percent.
</P>
<P>
Bank Indonesia expects the country's inflation rate in 2000 to
reach between three and five percent. It, however, warned that its
estimate for the inflation rate did not yet include any increases
in fuel and power prices, civil servants' wages or import duties
on rice and sugar.
</P>
<P>
He said that the positive trend had not yet encouraged maximum
development in the real sector, so that the economic recovery
process continued to proceed slowly.
</P>
<P>
"The business sector is still facing various hindrances," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Restructuring of foreign debts had not yet been finished, while
working capital was not available because banks were not yet
functioning well, he said.
</P>
<P>
Up to September 1999, Indonesia's foreign debts reached 145.2
billion U.S. dollars, a little lower than 1998's 150.9 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Sabirin said the country's GDP (Gross Domestic Product) in 1999
was only recorded at 0.1 percent or far below that recorded by
other crisis-hit Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
Exports were still low because investment activities were still
hindered, he said, adding that a surplus of 5.2 billion dollars in
the balance of payments in 1999 was caused by a drop in the import
value and better oil and gas exports.
</P>
<P>
Bank Indonesia predicted that current transactions in the
balance of payments will experience a surplus of 3.7 billion
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000106.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Budget Impasse Perplexes Philippine Govt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Congress failed to
pass the government-proposed 2000 national budget before the year-
end of 1999, which is believed to affect the country's economic
recovery process from Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Existing law of the Philippines provides that if the 2000
budget is not enacted at the start of a new fiscal year, the
previous year's budget automatically comes in force and will
remain so until the new budget is enacted.
</P>
<P>
The 1999 budget of the national government stood at 579.5
billion pesos (14.5 billion U.S. dollars), way below the 644
billion pesos (16.1 billion dollars) being eyed for the year 2000
by the government.
</P>
<P>
The House of Representatives approved last November a budget of
651 billion pesos (16.3 billion dollars) proposed by the
government, but the Senate cut it to 599 billion pesos (15 billion
dollars).
</P>
<P>
After Philippine President Joseph Estrada exerted pressure,
senators and congressmen agreed to contain the cuts to 7 billion
pesos (175 million dollars), putting the budget for 2000 at 644
billion pesos during the bicameral meetings.
</P>
<P>
However, senator John Osmena, chair of the Senate finance
committee, refused to sign what he called a "bloated" 644-billion-
peso budget. Without Osmena's signature, the proposed budget would
not get approved.
</P>
<P>
As pointed by some analysts, the budget impasse was basically
caused by the fight between those who were arguing for the needs
of specific agencies and sectors on one hand, and those arguing
for fiscal discipline and macroeconomic stability on the other.
</P>
<P>
Heads of government agencies and chiefs of local government
units managed to protect the allocations for their respective
turfs, saying the 644-billion-peso budget is important for the
recovery of the economy and the maintenance of the public service.
</P>
<P>
President Estrada said the budget is vital to his
administration's efforts to pump prime the economy which is
estimated to grow by 3.5 percent in 1999 as measured by the gross
national product (GNP) and expected to grow by 4.5 percent to 5.5
percent by year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Budget Secretary Benjami Diokno pointed out that the proposed
budget cut would have a negative impact on the economy because it
means "a negative growth in government consumption expenditures
and a negative growth in public and capital formation."
</P>
<P>
The government also worried that the proposed budget cut would
have serious social impact.
</P>
<P>
Jose Lina, who is the president of the 1.2 million-strong Union
of Local Authorities of the Philippines, has threatened to wage a
nationwide strike if the Congress would cut the 30 billion pesos (
750 million dollars) set for the local governments.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, some senators argued that the budget cut is
necessary, saying that the country's projected revenues cannot
justify the size of the national budget proposed by the
administration.
</P>
<P>
Defending his refusal to sign the budget report, Senator John
Osmena said passing an inadequately funded budget would result in
a deficit much bigger than the maximum 62.5 billion pesos (1.56
billion dollars) imposed by the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
Senate Majority Leader Franklin Drilon said that passing the 64-
billion-peso budget would widen the country's deficit to 92.5
billion pesos (2.3 billion dollars) in 2000.
</P>
<P>
They argued that a large budget deficit will force government
to borrow both domestically and internationally. That will soon
force interest and inflation rates up. It will weaken the currency
and finally hurt the prospects of the economy.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the IMF, expressing concern over the government's
failure to contain the deficit in 1999, is waiting for the outcome
of the budget dispute to decide if it will provide concessional
loans to assist the country's growth program.
</P>
<P>
Owing to the decline in tax collection, the budget deficit of
the country ballooned to 110 billion pesos (2.75 billion dollars)
as of last November, much higher than the 86-billion-peso (2.15
billion dollars) limit agreed by the government and the IMF.
</P>
<P>
To save the budget, the government is trying to assure the
Congress that it could find new resources to cover the deficit,
including selling the government shares in companies, imposing new
taxes, as well as seeking grants and aids abroad.
</P>
<P>
By now, the Presidential Palace remains optimistic that the 644-
billion-peso budget will finally be passed when the Congress
convenes for a special session on January 10-15.
</P>
<P>
But some economists pointed out that the country could be
headed for a "fiscal crisis" if the government continues to ignore
the much deeper problems in the way it manages its financial
affairs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
