<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania's Trade Deficit Drops, Trade Volume Continues to Contract </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Romania's foreign trade
deficit dropped by 51 percent in the first 10 months last year
while its trade volume continued to contract.
</P>
<P>
Latest data released Wednesday by the State Statistics
Committee said that the country's two-way trade from January to
October was 15.07 billion U.S. dollars. Its exports totaled 6.85
billion dollars and imports 8.22 billion dollars, dropping by 1
percent and 15.4 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
The trade deficit in the period under review was 1.37 billion
dollars compared with a year-ago level of 2.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
Dealers here were concerned about the contraction in foreign
trade, saying that export reduction that started early 1990 has
sharply eroded the country's external payment capabilities.
</P>
<P>
The steady decline in imports, particularly those of the state-
of-the-art technology and equipment, will inevitably whittle away
economic development potentials and have a negative impact on the
country's future development.
</P>
<P>
Statistics said that textile materials, textile products,
metallurgical products, machinery and shoes constitute the bulk of
Romanian exports while its main imports include machinery, textile,
mineral products and chemical products.
</P>
<P>
Transactions with its major trading partners, including Italy,
Germany, France, Britain, Russia, the Untied States and Hungary,
accounted for 60 percent of Romania's total trade.
</P>
<P>
Private businesses are playing an increasingly important role
in foreign trade, accounting for 73.5 percent in import and 66.5
percent in export, greatly surpassing the previous year level of
50 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
