<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Star Swimming Van Dyken Has Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Amy Van Dyken of the United
States, who won four gold medals at the 1996 Olympics, was resting
Wednesday after doctors remove scar tissue of her injured right
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
"The doctors said it went as expected, and she's going into
rehabilitation tomorrow," Van Dyken's agent Janey Miller said.
</P>
<P>
Van Dyken, 27, was expected to undergo 8-12 weeks of
rehabilitation before going back the water in March. Van Dyken
hopes she can be able to defend 50-meter freestyle title in the
Sydney Olympics in the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
"This is obviously a setback in my preparation for the 2000
Olympics," Van Dyken said, "but I have shown in the past that I
can come back from surgery just as strong as before. I should be
back in the pool in March and plan on swimming in Sydney."
</P>
<P>
Van Dyken had surgery before to her right shoulder, which she
tore in May 1998, five months after she won three gold medals in
the world championships.
</P>
<P>
She recovered in March 1999 and finished No.2 in the world list
for the 50m freestyle last summer. But her shoulder still bothered
her.
</P>
<P>
Van Dyken was a star of the Atlanta Games, becoming the first
American woman to win four Olympic gold medals in one year.
</P>
</TEXT>
