<HEADLINE> East China Province to Improve Exports Mix </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, January 6 (Xinhua) -- East China's coastal province of
Shandong, which ranks third in the country in terms of GDP, will
take measures to improve the mix of its export commodities to
secure a larger share of the international market.
</P>
<P>
An official with the provincial government said that advanced
technology and managerial expertise will be introduced from abroad
to accelerate the effort.
</P>
<P>
International quality standards will be widely employed in the
province's traditional industries of paper-making, textiles,
building materials, and ceramics.
</P>
<P>
Priority will be given to creating some eight famous brands for
textiles and garments, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The province will also upgrade the fine processing of farm
produce, poultry and aquatic products to reduce exports of raw
farm produce, the official added.
</P>
<P>
Shandong's 1999 export and import volume reached 18.1 billion U.
S. dollars, up 8.8 percent over 1998, according to statistics.
</P>
</TEXT>
