<HEADLINE> Charlton Hit Back at Man United Director  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Bobby Charlton has hit back at
claims by chairman Martin Edwards that the club would rather be
back in England playing in the FA Cup than competing in the
inaugural World Club Championship in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
Instead, the Manchester United director and former England star
believes United should grab the chance to create a slice of
footballing history.
</P>
<P>
Charlton said: "History will show, once again, that we were
right to accept the new challenge - we have the chance to write a
new page in history by becoming the first winners of the World
Club Championship."
</P>
<P>
He added: "When Sir Matt Busby saw the importance of competing
in Europe in the 1950s it did not go down well with the little
Englanders who thought we should stick to domestic football.
</P>
<P>
"And it is sometimes forgotten that England did not enter the
early World Cups and I cannot believe that there is anyone today
who would defend that decision."
</P>
<P>
But Charlton believes United's task shouldn't be underestimated
as they prepare to face Mexican side Necaxa in the first of their
group games on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Winning in Brazil will not be easy as the hot and humid
conditions will be alien to the English style of play.
</P>
<P>
"But I cannot believe anyone in England would not take some
pride when an English team can truly say it is the best in the
world - in any sport, not just football," he said. 
</P>
