<HEADLINE> Nigerian Maintains Condemnation of Coup in Cote d'Ivoire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Foreign Minister Alhaji
Sule Lamido said Wednesday that his government maintains its
condemnation of the military take-over in Cote d'Ivoire.
</P>
<P>
Lamido, who is among 10 ministers sent to Abidjanent Henri
Konan Bedie.
</P>
<P>
He noted that if military coups are left unchallenged, "then
democracy would never see the light of day as soldiers could just
wake up one morning and use force to bring down a government
chosen by the people."
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian minister urged the military junta of Cote d'Ivoire
to restore democracy within the shortest time, saying that six
months would be enough for the junta to hand over power to
civilians, as it was done in Mali and recently in Niger.
</P>
<P>
Lamido pointed out that Nigeria, which has just emerged from
15- year military rule, would be willing to assist Cote d'Ivoire
to restore democracy. 
</P>
