<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Border Authorities Said to Be Alerted to Arrest Hijackers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan reiterated Wednesday
that it has alerted its border authorities to be vigilant and
arrest the hijackers of an Indian airliner if they attempt to
cross into its territory.
</P>
<P>
A Foreign Office spokesman said, "Pakistan remains firm on its
intent to try the hijackers in accordance with the law. Border
authorities have been alerted to maintain strict vigilance in
order to arrest the hijackers if they attempt to enter Pakistan."
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, since the end of the hijacking on
the last day of the past millennium, the Indian government has not
made any contact with the government of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Throughout the episode, the government of Pakistan has
condemned all acts of terrorism including hijacking and provided
all assistance to India which was initially appreciated by India,
said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
However, he charged that India has failed to provide any
evidence or any relevant information to Pakistan which would
facilitate the arrest of the hijackers or prove that they had any
links in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
"Lack of any information regarding their identity has so far
frustrated attempts to find them," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also asked New Delhi to make available the transcripts of
the negotiations conducted with the hijackers by Indian
negotiators at Kandahar Airport of Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Indian Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee has repeatedly
accused Pakistan of involvement in the hijacking of the Indian
Airlines plane which had been stranded in Afghanistan for seven
days with more than 150 hostages on board.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman called such accusations an "Indian propaganda
campaign against Pakistan" and "a crude attempt to externalize her
own problems."
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Afghanistan's ruling Taliban, who dealt with the
hijacking drama along with India, had refuted the Indian
allegation that the hijackers were Pakistanis and they had left
for Quetta, the spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
