<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bahraini Emir Visits Qatar for Closer Bilateral Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Bahraini Emir Sheikh Hamad
Bin Isa Al-Khalifa arrived in the Qatari capital of Doha Thursday
to further the recently improved ties between the two Gulf Arab
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
The Bahraini Emir's brief visit came nine days after Qatar's
Emir Sheikh Hamad Bin Khalifa Al-Thani's tour of Bahrain on
December 28, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The two emirs agreed in the Bahraini capital of Manama to
exchange ambassadors and to set up a joint committee to try to
settle a border dispute through cordial means.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival, the Bahraini Emir described the Manama meeting
as "historic, successful and distinguished."
</P>
<P>
He said the door of cooperation between the two countries is
wide open now at both the government and private levels and in the
political, economic, social and cultural fields.
</P>
<P>
Qatar and Bahrain are locked in a dispute over several small but
potentially oil- and gas-rich Gulf isles, including the Hawar
islands, which are controlled by Bahrain since 1930s but also
claimed by Qatar.
</P>
<P>
The issue has been taken to the International Court of Justice,
which is expected to begin hearings on it next May.
</P>
<P>
A joint statement issued after the Manama meeting said the two
emirs agreed that the case will be withdrawn if an acceptable
solution is reached before the court's verdict by the joint
committee, which is co-chaired by their crown princes.
</P>
<P>
They stressed the long-running border standoff should not hamper
bilateral cooperation in other fields.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also agreed to resume Qatari Airlines' flights
between Doha and Manama.
</P>
<P>
According to reports reaching here earlier Thursday, the
Bahraini Emir will hold talks with his Qatari counterpart on
bilateral cooperation, and the Gulf, Arab and international issues.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is also expected to set a date for the first meeting
of the newly-formed joint committee.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
