<HEADLINE> Clinton to Return to Syrian-Israeli Talks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHEPHERDSTOWN, W. Va., January 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President
Bill Clinton planned to return to Shepherdstown, West Virginia,
Thursday afternoon to try to help Syrians and Israelis speed up
their work, State Department spokesman James Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said Clinton was returning to the Syrian-Israeli peace
talks at the request of Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
"Secretary Albright has recommended that the president return
today to help the parties and help her get the parties rolling up
their sleeves and proceeding to do the substantive work in a
professional and hopefully soon in accelerated way," he said.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said the two sides did not hold any working committee
meetings Thursday and Clinton's return might help bring them to
direct discussions.
</P>
<P>
"We didn't seek committee meetings this morning because we
think the best needs this morning are for the substantive work to
go on informally through direct contacts by us with the parties,"
Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
Two committees on security and peace term started working
Wednesday while other two on borders and water have not yet
convened.
</P>
<P>
Direct contacts mean that Syrians and Israelis sit face to face.
"Informal contacts" is the U.S. term for separate talks between
the United States and the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Albright met with Syrian Foreign Minister Faruk Shareh for 45
minutes Thursday, according to a Syrian sources.
</P>
<P>
He said Shareh asserted that all core issues should be taken up
simultaneously in line with the agreed mechanism that said all
four committees would meet concurrently. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
