<HEADLINE> U.S. Special Commission Announces Presidential Debate Sites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 6 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. nonpartisan special
commission announced here Thursday sites and dates for three
presidential debates this fall.
</P>
<P>
The Commission on Presidential Debates announced that the three
debates will be held at the John F. Kennedy Library and University
of Massachusetts in Boston on October 3, Wake Forest University in
Winston-Salem, North Carolina on October 11 and Washington
University in St. Louis on October 17.
</P>
<P>
There also will be one vice-presidential debate on October 5 at
Center College in Danville, Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
The commission ruled that it would exclude any candidate who
didn't have at least 15 percent support in national polls, making
it difficult for a third-party candidate or anyone else besides
the Republican and Democratic nominees to get on the stage for the
nationally televised debates.
</P>
<P>
The commission was created in 1987 to sponsor general election
presidential and vice-presidential debates.  
</P>
</TEXT>
