<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Motorola Demonstrates Multicolor Phone Displays </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Bright colors help the user distinguish various icons,
improving the display's readability in all conditions, whether in
office lighting, low light, or total darkness.
</P>
<P>
"The new Organic Electro-Luminescent (OEL) color display offers
an important benefit to cell phone users, and continues to
position Motorola at the forefront of innovative wireless product
technology," said Ralph Pini, senior vice president and general
manager for Motorola's Personal Communications Sector's Product
Realization Group.
</P>
<P>
"Better readability is especially important as we move to
wireless web browsers that pack a lot of information onto a phone'
s display," he added.
</P>
<P>
The OEL display, developed in partnership with Pioneer Corp.,
of Japan, is one of the first demonstrations of this technology in
a portable product. It is based on light emitting structures that
can be patterned with the same resolution as conventional LCD
displays.
</P>
<P>
The result is a bright graphic display that can be easily read
in any lighting condition. This display utilizes an energy-
efficient architecture with very economical power consumption --
meaning negligible impact on standby or talk time.
</P>
<P>
Motorola plans to debut the OEL display technology in a phone
in the first half of 2000.
</P>
<P>
More than 90,000 pre-registered industry members are expected
to attend the 2000 Consumer Electronic Show between January 6 and
9, the largest of its kind in its 32-year history since 1967.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000106.0320 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECGD Backing Puts Marconi Deal In China On Track </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Britain announced Thursday the
Export Credits Guarantee Department (ECGD) backing for a contract
won in China by Coventry-based Marconi Communications China
Limited.
</P>
<P>
ECGD is Britain's official export credit agency. Its main
functions are to underwrite bank loans to enable overseas buyers
to purchase capital and project related goods and services from
Britain.
</P>
<P>
Marconi has been given an order by China's Ministry of Railways
to supply, install and commission Synchronous Digital Hierarchy (
SDH) digital optic fiber transmission equipment, according to the
announcement.
</P>
<P>
ECGD has underwritten a 26 million U.S. dollars loan from ANZ
Investment Bank to the China Development Bank to help finance the
deal.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time a contract awarded by China's Ministry
of Railways has been financed by the use of export credit, ECGD
said.
</P>
<P>
Richard Caborn, the British Minister for Trade, said: "This is
another fine example of the excellent trading relations the UK now
has with China. I am delighted that Marconi is building on past
success in the market with the help of ECGD."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000106.0321 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Korean Crash Cargo Contained Depleted Uranium: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Korean Air Boeing 747 cargo
plane, which crashed last month near an airport north of London,
contained several hundred kilograms of depleted uranium, it was
revealed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Depleted uranium (DU) is a heavy substance, 1.7 times as dense
as lead. It has also been used in aircraft to make counterweights
in the tailplane.
</P>
<P>
"If no precautions were taken at the crash scene, people will
have been exposed to hazards that could prove fatal," Malcolm
Hooper ,professor emeritus of medicinal chemistry at the
University of Sunderland, told BBC News Online.
</P>
<P>
A Boeing spokesman said that the company began using DU in the
early 1960s.
</P>
<P>
"Boeing replaced it with tungsten in the early 1980s on grounds
of cost and availability. The Korean 747 was delivered to the
airline in June 1980. We think it contained about 300 kg of DU,"
the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
More than 800 residents and rescue workers were reported after
the crash to be complaining of a range of problems, including
fatigue, skin complaints, joint and bone pains, kidney ailments
and respiratory problems. 
</P>
