<HEADLINE> Dow Continues To Rise But Nasdaq Falls Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 130.61 at 11,253.26.
The blue chip index rose 124.72 points Wednesday, rebounding from
a steep drop of 359.58 points Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index rose 1.34 at 1,403.45 and the technology heavy Nasdaq
composite index fell 150.41 at 3,727.13.
</P>
<P>
The market made a reversal Thursday as investors bought
cyclical shares while selling technology stocks. The Dow was led
by Caterpillar, 3M and Procter &AMP; Gamble, which were seen as safer
bets if the Federal Reserve raises interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Investors continued to sell technology stocks to take profits
from strong rallies in the final days of 1999. The index rose to
an unheard-of 85.6 percent gains last year.
</P>
<P>
The warnings about lower profits for two high-tech companies
also helped to drag the Nasdaq index lower. Personal computer
maker Gateway warned late Wednesday its fourth-quarter earnings
would miss expectations due to a slowdown in sales while a Wall
Street analyst said MCI Worldcom's revenue is likely to grow 14.4
percent from 1999 to 2000, below his previous estimate of 15.2
percent.
</P>
<P>
But analysts expected technology stocks to bounce back after
plunging because technology companies still have great potential
for making money. The index fell 404.02 points or 9.7 percent in
the three sessions since Tuesday this year.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE rose 6.47 at 627.54. But the American Stock Exchange
index fell 1.12 at 857.76 and the Russell 2000 index of smaller
companies fell 3.49 at 475.34.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 5-to-3 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,974 up, 1,158 down and 410
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased to 1.08 billion shares from 1.07 billion
in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
