<DOCNO> XIE20000106.0329 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sales of Traditional Lifestyle Products to Remain Strong in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Sales of traditional
lifestyle products will remain strong in the United States this
year, despite an expected decline of sales of audio products,
according to a report released Thursday by the Consumer
Electronics Association (CEA).
</P>
<P>
The U.S. trade organization expected total sales of consumer
electronics products in the United States to hit a record 85
billion U.S. dollars in 2000. The CEA breaks up consumer
electronics into traditional lifestyle products, and home
information category which includes PCs and peripherals,
telephones, pagers and digital cameras.
</P>
<P>
Among traditional lifestyle products, digital versatile disc (
DVD) players, within the video category, are expected to continue
their phenomenal growth. In 1999, DVD players became the fastest
selling product in the U.S. history of consumer electronics, with
more than 4 million units sold during the year. This figure is up
371 percent over 1998 sales. The CEA projected sales of roughly 1.
5 billion U.S. dollars in 2000 with some 6.5 million units
expected to be sold.
</P>
<P>
Television will continue to stand as the centerpiece of home
consumer electronics with more than 42 million TVs to be sold in
2000.
</P>
<P>
Sales of direct-to-home satellite systems also are expected to
climb in 2000, with system installations to reach 4.1 million from
3.6 million in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The report said that sales of home and portable audio products
will decline by 3 percent. But with more than 5.6 billion dollars
in projected sales for 2000, audio products remain a popular
choice for consumers. CD players top the list of audio best-
sellers with 47 million players to be sold in 2000.
</P>
<P>
American consumers continue to demand access to information and
entertainment as well as stay in touch with friends and family
while on the go, the report said. Sales of mobile electronics will
reach 9.1 million dollars. Autosound equipment will top 4.9
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Sales of gaming hardware and software are expected to rise by
16 percent in 2000, following a five-year period in which sales
have increased about 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to the CEA, the average American household spends 1,
000 dollars per year on consumer electronics -- twice as much as
it spends on furniture, toys, sporting good or jewelry.
</P>
<P>
Color televisions are in 98 percent of all U.S. households.
More than 93 million U.S. households own at least one VCR, while
98 million households own a home radio, according to the report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000106.0330 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DVD-Video Becomes Fastest-Growing Products In North America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAS VEGAS, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Enjoying even greater sales
than expected in the past two years or so, DVD-Video was hailed as
the most successful consumer electronics product launched ever in
North America, according to statistics released at the on-going
2000 Consumer Electronics Show here.
</P>
<P>
Figures released Thursday by the DVD Entertainment Group
estimate that hardware player sales sold through to consumers
since the format launched in late 1997 have reached 5.4 million
players in the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
Industry executives named DVD-Video the "Medium of the
Millennium" and boast that DVD-Video is the fastest-growing new
packaged media format launched in history.
</P>
<P>
The outlook for next year is equally promising. The DVD
Entertainment Group estimated that hardware shipments will double
to 8 million DVD-Video players in 2000. And, based on the success
of the format exceeding all previous forecasts, that number could
be even higher.
</P>
<P>
The group also estimated that the installed base will more than
exceed 10 percent of U.S. households, a benchmark of success for a
consumer electronics product.
</P>
<P>
The surge in hardware sales is a positive boost for retailers.
In 1999, DVD-Video hardware represented more than 1 billion
dollars in retail sales. This includes stand-alone players only
and does not include DVD-ROM drives or other home theater products.
</P>
<P>
In only its third year in the marketplace, DVD-Video player
prices have declined significantly. Statistics show the average
price sold for a DVD-Video player was 298 dollars last November,
down 30 percent from 428 dollars at the same time last year. Some
players and models are available for less than 200 dollars, making
the format accessible to the mass market.
</P>
<P>
Joe Pagano, vice president in charge of merchandising for Best
Buy, attributed the spectacular results to enthusiastic
acceptance by the consumer, reduction of hardware prices, the
release of popular titles such as "The Matrix," "Saving Private
Ryan" and "The Mummy," and the introduction of "Disney Classics."
</P>
<P>
The DVD Entertainment Group estimated that DVD-Video brought in
revenue of more than 2 billion dollars for Hollywood studios and
music labels in 1999. According to figures compiled by Ernst &AMP;
Young on behalf of the DVD Entertainment Group, nearly 100 million
DVD movies and music videos were shipped in 1999.
</P>
<P>
In the fourth quarter alone, almost 50 million DVD movies and
music videos were shipped to retail. This figure represents
virtually the same amount that were shipped in the first nine
months of 1999 and is a 400 percent growth over the same period in
1998.
</P>
<P>
Since the format's launch, software shipments have reached more
than 130 million units, according to the DVD Entertainment Group.
</P>
<P>
The DVD Entertainment Group expected the industry to double its
1999 sales by shipping at least 200 million DVD movies and music
videos in 2000, representing 4 billion dollars in revenue for the
studios and music labels, approximately half of the total revenue
generated from the VHS sell-through. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000106.0331 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Criticizes Italy for Untreated Waste Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission (EC)
Thursday came a step closer to reporting Italy to the European
Court of Justice for the untreated Milanese sewage water that is
polluting the River Po and the Adriatic Sea.
</P>
<P>
According to Italian news agency Ansa, the commission sent a "
motivated opinion" to the Italian government on the matter, the
last step before turning to the court in Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
Milan is the only major European city that is still discharging
untreated sewage waters directly into a key waterway, the Lambro
Olona, which runs into the Po.
</P>
<P>
The EC said this "contributes significantly" to the pollution
of the river and to the thick algae that is choking the oxygen out
of the Adriatic, threatening fish stocks and the tourist industry.
</P>
<P>
The commission said Milan should have taken adequate measures
to comply with a European Union (EU) directive by the end of 1998,
installing purification plants.
</P>
<P>
As things stand, it will not be able to meet EU standards until
the end of 2002 at the earliest, the EC claims.
</P>
<P>
Three water treatment plants are being built around Milan but
they are due to start operating between 2002 and 2005, "well
beyond the deadline," the EC said.
</P>
<P>
"Milan, one of the most important cities in Europe, is setting
a very bad example," said European Environment Commissioner Margot
Wallstrom.
</P>
<P>
"It's really disappointing that Milan should continue to be
without a proper water treatment system, especially in such a
sensitive river basin as the Po's," she added.
</P>
<P>
The EU's 1999 directive requires European cities to meet EU
standards on water treatment by 1998, 2000 or 2005, according to
the size of the city (with the smallest complying last).
</P>
<P>
With a population of 2.7 million, Milan is in the first group,
the major cities that should have brought their treatment systems
up to scratch by 1998.
</P>
<P>
Inadequate treatment of sewage and waste water is one of the
main sources of river pollution across the EU, the commission said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
