<HEADLINE> Romanian Universities Asked to Give Up Entrance Exams </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Romania's Minister of National
Education Andrei Marga has recently asked universities all over
the country to give up the entrance exams starting this year, the
official Rompres news agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Thus, the students' admission in faculty will be made only
according to the average mark they got during high school years
and at the high school graduation exam.
</P>
<P>
Both students and universities could benefit from giving up the
entrance exam. On the one hand, students will get rid of an extra
exam shortly after the graduation exam, and on the other hand,
universities will cut expenses as organizing such entrance
examinations costs quite a lot.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the Ministry of Education announced its intention to
increase the number of seats in the academic education, but the
exact figure will be known only after the budget for this year is
approved. There were 105,000 seats with state universities in 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
