<HEADLINE> Record Growth in U.S. Consumer Electronics Sales in 2000 Projected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Total sales of consumer
electronics products in the United States will hit a record 85
billion U.S. dollars in 2000, according to projections released
Thursday by the Consumer Electronics Association (CEA).
</P>
<P>
This figure represents the eighth consecutive year of growth
for the industry. The CEA, a sector of the U.S. trade organization
Electronic Industries Alliance, also expected total consumer
electronics sales in the U.S. to reach 81 billion dollars in 1999,
up 7 percent over the 1998 figure of 75 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
"Consumers continue to embrace the exciting array of products
made possible by digital technology," said the CEA in the forecast
report. "We anticipate even further growth as the lines between
traditional information technology and consumer electronics
products blur, enabling manufacturers to offer new products to
enhance consumers' workstyles and lifestyles."
</P>
<P>
Reflecting consumers' continuing desire for workstyle
technologies -- products that enable them to work when, where and
how they wish, the home information category is projected to grow
by 6.5 percent in 2000, with sales of 37 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Within this category, the CEA estimated that a full 54 percent
of all U.S. households own a personal computer. Total PC sales
will hit a record of 16.8 billion dollars in 2000 with 16.8
million units expected to be sold. Sales of computer printers,
modems and fax modems, monitors and other computer peripherals
will add another 10 billion dollars in sales to the computer
hardware category. PC software will surpass 5.2 billion dollars in
sales, marking a full 16 percent rise from 1999.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere within the home information category, sales of corded
and cordless telephones will hit 80 million units or 2.4 billion
dollars. Sales of wireless telephones are expected to reach 18
million units.
</P>
<P>
Sales of traditional lifestyle products also will remain strong
in 2000 in the United States, the report said. These include video
and audio products, television, gaming hardware and software.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
