<DOCNO> XIE20000106.0337 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese, U.S. Companies To Create Set-Top-Box Converter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The announcement was made at the 2000 Consumer Electronics Show
in Las Vegas, which is expected to draw more than 90,000 pre-
registered industry members and more than 100,000 visitors between
January 6 and 9.
</P>
<P>
Funai and Sarnoff said they will work together to develop a
customized set-top-box solution which Funai will manufacture.
Distribution is expected to begin in the fourth quarter of 2000.
</P>
<P>
Funai is a major provider of TVs and VCRs under the Funai,
Symphonic and Sylvania brand names and an Original Equipment
Manufacturer supplier of sets for sale under other well-known
brands.
</P>
<P>
Sarnoff's role under the agreement includes developing a
customized graphical user interface and a reference design
targeted at the mass market. The proposed set-top box will include
the Motorola MCT 2100 demodulator and MCT 4100 video decoder chips
for reliable reception and superior video quality. The chips were
designed by Motorola in partnership with Sarnoff.
</P>
<P>
"We are excited about the market prospects for affordable DTV
converters, and pleased to be working with a leading developer of
DTV technology," said Mr. S. Otsuka, executive director of Funai.
</P>
<P>
"Our set-top converter box will allow consumers to receive
terrestrial DTV broadcasts on their current analog TVs and home
theaters, with outstanding digital quality pictures and sound, at
a price that will be very attractive in the mass market," he added.
</P>
<P>
The product will offer reception of both ATSC digital and NTSC
analog broadcasts without manual switching by the user.
</P>
<P>
"Funai is a leader in TV and VCR manufacturing, and we're very
happy to be working with them," said James E. Carnes, president
and CEO of Sarnoff. "With their remarkable production capabilities
the consumer can look forward to a high-quality product."
</P>
<P>
According to Funai, this converter is the first in a line of
DTV/HDTV solutions planned for introduction over the next few
years.
</P>
<P>
Set-top converter boxes for DTV effectively turn an analog TV
into a display for digital content, giving consumers access to
digital television programming and such DTV features as CD-quality
surround sound.
</P>
<P>
Funai sees the over 250 million analog TVs in American homes
today as a huge potential market for popularly-priced versions of
set-top boxes, especially as DTV programming availability
increases. More than 100 DTV stations are currently on the air,
reaching over 50 percent of the U.S. population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
