<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish PM to Initiate Constitutional Amendment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister Bulent
Ecevit said on Thursday that he stands for an extension of
President Suleyman Demirel's term which will end on May 16,
reported the Anatolia News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit declared that he will launch a campaign to amend the
Constitution to allow for such a move.
</P>
<P>
Emerging from his weekly meeting with Demirel, the prime
minister said that he is the first person to have voiced the need
for Demirel's term to be extended, adding he raised the issue with
the president for the first time during their meeting Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit stressed that this is his personal idea and that the
president has never expressed such a desire nor has given such a
hint.
</P>
<P>
"As a member of past governments and as prime minister, I have
personally witnessed that the president, with his vast experience,
has served this country with great success, both at home and
abroad," said Ecevit.
</P>
<P>
Reasoning his initiative, Ecevit said that Turkey is going
through a period of stability in which confidence is at an all-time
high at home and that the country is held in high esteem
abroad.  "Stability in our country depends on sensitive
balances, and I believe that if the term of office of President
Demirel is extended for another term, this will further strengthen
the atmosphere of stability," he added.
</P>
<P>
Demirel, who was elected by Parliament on May 16, 1993 for a
seven-year term according to the Constitution, must leave office on
May 17. However, a constitutional amendment will permit him to stay
on in office.
</P>
<P>
Demirel has called for a change in the Constitution to allow
the president to be elected by the people directly. However, in
recent weeks he did not raise any objections to his term in office
being prolonged by Parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
