<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright to Attend Middle East Meeting in Moscow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright will attend the ministerial meeting of the
multilateral Middle East peace talks in Moscow on February 1,
State Department spokesman James Rubin said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In Jerusalem, Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov announced
earlier that the U.S. and Russia will co-chair the ministerial
meeting.
</P>
<P>
"The purpose of the meeting will be to mark the formal revival
and to resume the work of the multilateral-track peace process,"
Rubin told reporters at a briefing in Shepherdstown, West Virginia,
where Syria and Israel are in the fourth day of peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said that Albright will also meet senior Russian
officials on important issues of arms control, nonproliferation,
regional issues and economic reform.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman confirmed that the meeting will be held at the
level of foreign ministers from countries including the core
regional parties like Egypt, Israel, Jordan, Palestine, Saudi
Arabia, Tunisia, Syria, Lebanon, as well as Canada, the European
Union, Japan and Norway, as key international supporters of the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that invitations have not been sent out.
Russia and the U.S, co-sponsors of Middle East peace talks
launched in Madrid in 1991, have consulted each other on possible
participants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
