<DOCNO> XIE20000106.0346 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Emerging Market Economies Providing Better Information to Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Many authorities have made
progress in providing the capital markets with improved data on
their economies, according to a new report released Thursday by
the Institute of International Finance (IIF).
</P>
<P>
The IIF said that its survey of the data release practices of
27 leading emerging market economies shows high levels of
reporting against 25 key IIF benchmarks by a number of economies
including Argentina, the Czech Republic, Poland, Peru, Thailand,
and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
"Improved information to lenders and investors is reinforcing
the stability of the international financial system," said John
Bond, the IIF's chairman and chairman of HSBC Holdings Plc.
</P>
<P>
The IIF report, "Data Release Practices of Emerging Market
Economies: 1999 Assessment," indicated that following the 1997
Asian crisis, a number of Asian economies acted to significantly
strengthen their data release approaches.
</P>
<P>
"The crises in certain emerging market economies over the last
few years have once again highlighted the need for the markets to
have greater data transparency from the leading borrowing
countries. Our survey found that constructive responses to market
expectations are being made by a growing number of these countries,
" said Charles Dallara, the IIF's managing director.
</P>
<P>
The IIF, the global association of financial institutions with
315 members, initiated emerging market benchmark standards in 1995
and its most recently published comprehensive assessment was in
1997.
</P>
<P>
The benchmarks have been strengthened following the March 1999
report of a working group involving representatives of leading
financial institutions. Reinforcement of the standard included the
introduction of a requirement for weekly rather than monthly data
on reserves; additional data on disposition of reserves and drains
on them; and more demanding standards for debt, including short-
term debt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
