<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania to Sell T-bills Worth 750 Million Dollars in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Romanian Finance Ministry
said it would recommence in mid-January negotiations with Merrill
Lynch and Nomura investment banks of launching two series of
treasury bills worth 250 million U.S. dollars and 500 million U.S.
dollars respectively, reported the local daily Ziarul Financiar on
Thursday quoting Finance Minister Decebal Traian Remes.
</P>
<P>
According to Valentin Lazea, chief economist of Romania's
central bank, Romania's foreign debt accounted for less than 25
percent of the Gross Domestic Product, leaving the country a gate
to loans from external capital markets.
</P>
<P>
Romania's present Prime Minister Mugur Isarescu in December
last year said in his capacity as a governor of the central bank
that Romania in 2000 would await foreign loans of up to one
billion U.S.dollars.
</P>
<P>
Romania this year must pay its foreign debt service of 2.22
billion U.S. dollars. In 1999, this debt amounted to a total of
about eight billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the Romanian Finance Ministry and Credit Suisse
First Boston struck a deal to issue treasury bills with interest
rates of about 12 percent, but the American-Swiss bank failed to
sell the bonds under 17 percent returns. In the same year,
negotiations between the Romanian government and Merrill Lynch for
a new bond issuance came to nought as well. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
