<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flu Cases Rise Again in Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The number of flu infections has
increased in Britain, according to the latest figures released
Thursday, but experts said there is little risk of an epidemic.
</P>
<P>
The weekly statistics released by the Public Health Laboratory
Service showed a small increase in the number of people suffering
from the virus in England, suggesting the illness is nearing its
seasonal peak.
</P>
<P>
But despite not reaching epidemic levels, intensive care units
across Britain were under enormous pressure. The problem appears
to be exacerbated by a shortage of nurses in the National Health
Service.
</P>
<P>
In England, the number of reported cases rose from 124 per 100,
000 population last week to 144 this week.
</P>
<P>
Anything less than 400 is not classed as an epidemic.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday was the busiest day of the winter so far for London
hospitals in terms of demands on beds and the need to transfer
patients between hospitals.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, there were only 11 vacant intensive care beds in
the whole of the UK.
</P>
<P>
All the 275 beds in London's major hospitals were reported to
be occupied.
</P>
<P>
Many hospitals have already been forced to cancel planned
surgery because no intensive care facilities are available for
patients following their operations.
</P>
<P>
In London, some patients have been forced to wait up to 20
hours for treatment as casualty departments are inundated with
patients suffering from respiratory disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
